#: content/_index.md:64
msgid "What’s in it for you"
msgstr ""

#: content/_index.md:65
msgid ""
"Remember when Linux was an undiscovered country and everything was new and "
"fun? KDE Linux is that all over again: we’re creating the operating system "
"of the future with the clout and resources of KDE behind it, and you can be "
"part of it. Here, individual efforts make a difference on a global scale."
msgstr ""

#: content/_index.md:67
msgid ""
"{{< linux/button src=\"/docs/kde-linux-dev\" description=\"Contribute to KDE"
" Linux\" >}} {{< /section >}}"
msgstr ""

#: content/_index.md:74
msgid "<div class=\"text-center\">\n"
msgstr ""

#: content/_index.md:76
msgid "Things to be aware of"
msgstr ""

#: content/_index.md:78
msgid ""
"![Computer with squashed banana wallpaper](/linux/Computer-Screen-"
"_ripe_banana.png)"
msgstr ""

#: content/_index.md:79
msgid "</div>\n"
msgstr ""

#: content/_index.md:81
msgid ""
"**KDE Linux is Alpha software.** Do not install it on your non-technical "
"uncle’s computer or across the accounting department at work. There are "
"[multiple known issues](https://invent.kde.org/groups/kde-"
"linux/-/work_items?sort=created_date&state=opened&or%5Blabel_name%5D%5B%5D=High%20priority&or%5Blabel_name%5D%5B%5D=Significant%20user-"
"facing%20issue) (make sure nothing in there is a deal-breaker for you). KDE "
"Linux has only received limited testing so far, and there will be "
"regressions and bad builds you’ll have to roll back. Data loss has not been "
"experienced yet, but anything is possible. Deploy a robust backup system. "
"Expect some adventures."
msgstr ""

#: content/_index.md:82
msgid ""
"**Opportunities for customizing the base OS are extremely limited.** As an "
"“immutable base” operating system, KDE Linux deliberately limits system-"
"level customization to preserve reliability. Don’t go starting and stopping "
"Systemd services except to debug or fix reported bugs. Don’t try hacks to "
"customize your Plymouth splash screen or SDDM theme."
msgstr ""

#: content/_index.md:83
msgid ""
"**The experience of using an older NVIDIA GPU is rough.** [Manual "
"setup](/docs/pre-turing-nvidia) is currently required for anything older "
"than an NVIDIA GTX 1630 to even work at all, and they are essentially "
"untested. Here be dragons. You’ve been warned. [Learn more about this "
"situation here](/nvidia)."
msgstr ""

#: content/_index.md:84
msgid ""
"**Do not report bugs for yesterday’s version.** That’s right: currently KDE "
"Linux is being updated daily. If you think you found a bug… update the whole"
" system first! If the bug is still there, go ahead and report it. {{< "
"/section >}}"
msgstr ""

#: content/_index.md:89
msgid ""
"<div class=\"help-section d-flex flex-row\">\n"
"  <div id=\"help-other-distros\" class=\"w-50  g-0 p-0\">\n"
msgstr ""

#: content/_index.md:92
msgid ""
"If using an alpha-quality operating system isn’t your cup of tea, feel free "
"to install any of the released ones on the [Distributions "
"page](https://kde.org/distributions/)."
msgstr ""

#: content/_index.md:98
msgid "Key benefits"
msgstr ""

#: content/_index.md:103
msgid "Safe"
msgstr ""

#: content/_index.md:104
msgid ""
"KDE Linux offers reliable system updates and lets you roll back to older "
"versions if there are any issues."
msgstr ""

#: content/_index.md:106
msgid ""
"All code is open and auditable, and no data is ever sent to KDE unless you "
"authorize it. {{< /linux/card >}}"
msgstr ""

#: content/_index.md:110
msgid "Simple"
msgstr ""

#: content/_index.md:111
msgid ""
"The Plasma desktop environment is familiar and intuitive, offering panels, "
"app launchers, icons, and menus where you expect them. {{< /linux/card >}}"
msgstr ""

#: content/_index.md:115
msgid "Flexible"
msgstr ""

#: content/_index.md:116
msgid ""
"Set up the system the way *you* like with the customizability built into "
"Plasma. Show off your style or turn it into a high-productivity workhorse! "
"{{< /linux/card >}}"
msgstr ""

#: content/_index.md:120
msgid "Powerful"
msgstr ""

#: content/_index.md:121
msgid ""
"KDE Linux offers a rich catalogue of professional-caliber software for [any "
"purpose](https://kde.org/for/), all for free. {{< /linux/card >}}"
msgstr ""

#: content/_index.md:124
msgid "{{< /linux/cards >}} {{< /section >}}"
msgstr ""

#: content/_index.md:131
msgid "Compare KDE Linux to alternatives"
msgstr ""

#: content/_index.md:132
msgid ""
"KDE Linux has been designed to be highly competitive with contemporary "
"desktop operating systems. See if it’s right for you:"
msgstr ""

#: content/_index.md:134
msgid ""
"<details>\n"
"  <summary>Compare to Microsoft Windows™</summary>\n"
"  <article>\n"
"    <h4>Advantages:</h4>\n"
"    <ul>\n"
"      <li><strong>More secure:</strong> no spyware, kill-switches, or backdoors</li>\n"
"      <li><strong>Friendlier:</strong> no pop-up ads, forced AI functionality, or mandatory online accounts</li>\n"
"      <li><strong>Longer lasting:</strong> keep receiving updates no matter how old your computer is</li>\n"
"      <li><strong>More ergonomic:</strong> adapt it to your tastes and preferences</li>\n"
"      <li><strong>More efficient:</strong> faster, smaller installed size, and lower RAM, CPU, and GPU usage</li>\n"
"      <li><strong>More humane:</strong> free and open source, built by humans, for humans</li>\n"
"    </ul>\n"
"    <h4>Potential challenges:</h4>\n"
"    <ul>\n"
"      <li>Different software ecosystem, and some Windows-only software may be difficult to run. You can find alternatives in <em>Discover</em></li>\n"
"    </ul>\n"
"  </article>\n"
"</details>\n"
msgstr ""

#: content/_index.md:153
msgid ""
"<details>\n"
"  <summary>Compare to Apple MacOS™</summary>\n"
"  <article>\n"
"    <h4>Advantages:</h4>\n"
"    <ul>\n"
"      <li><strong>Longer lasting:</strong> keep receiving updates no matter how old your computer is</li>\n"
"      <li><strong>More ergonomic:</strong> adapt it to your tastes and preferences</li>\n"
"      <li><strong>Better multi-tasking:</strong> easier to manage lots of open apps and windows</li>\n"
"      <li><strong>More humane:</strong> free and open source, built by humans, for humans</li>\n"
"    </ul>\n"
"    <h4>Potential challenges:</h4>\n"
"    <ul>\n"
"      <li>Different software ecosystem; Mac-only software likely impossible to run. You can find alternatives in <em>Discover</em></li>\n"
"      <li>Ditching MacOS worsens the experience of using any remaining Apple devices</li>\n"
"    </ul>\n"
"  </article>\n"
"</details>\n"
msgstr ""

#: content/_index.md:171
msgid ""
"<details>\n"
"  <summary>Compare to other Linux-based operating systems</summary>\n"
"  <article>\n"
"    <h4>Advantages:</h4>\n"
"    <ul>\n"
"      <li><strong>Safety features:</strong> read-only <code>/usr</code>, transactional image-based updates, OS rollback, Btrfs snapshots for user files, and a built-in backup system</li>\n"
"      <li><strong>Good integration:</strong> KDE software straight from KDE, the way it was meant to be experienced</li>\n"
"      <li><strong>Easy app management:</strong> straightforward experience for installing and removing apps, and cleaning up leftovers from no-longer-installed apps</li>\n"
"    </ul>\n"
"    <h4>Potential challenges:</h4>\n"
"    <ul>\n"
"      <li>Potentially smaller app catalogue</li>\n"
"      <li>Potentially more limited support for arbitrary hardware</li>\n"
"      <li>No included CLI package manager</li>\n"
"    </ul>\n"
"    {{< alert color=\"success\" icon=\"tip\" >}}\n"
"KDE Linux is an “opinionated” and “immutable” operating system. If you know what these terms mean and they aren’t your cup of tea, you can find plenty of user-friendly KDE-focused operating systems with traditional package management tools [on the Distributions page](https://kde.org/distributions).\n"
msgstr ""

#: content/_index.md:189
msgid ""
"For even more options — including power-user operating system designed to be"
" built by hand and customized by highly opinionated technical experts — [see"
" the Distributions page on the KDE "
"wiki](https://community.kde.org/Distributions). {{< /alert >}}"
msgstr ""

#: content/_index.md:191
msgid ""
"  </article>\n"
"</details>\n"
msgstr ""

