#: content/docs/apps-and-games.md:0
msgid "Install Apps and Games"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/apps-and-games.md:11
msgid ""
"In KDE Linux, most software is packaged using a technology called "
"[Flatpak](https://flatpak.org/) and distributed through https://flathub.org."
" You can get this software in two ways: graphically using the _Discover_ "
"software center app, or using the <code>flatpak</code> command-line tool."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/apps-and-games.md:14 content/docs/updates.md:14
msgid "Graphical"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/apps-and-games.md:15
msgid ""
"_Discover_ is the primary tool for getting new software on KDE Linux. It’s "
"very easy to use; just launch it! You can use the search field to find "
"something specific, or browse through one of the categories in the sidebar "
"on the left side of the window."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/apps-and-games.md:17
msgid ""
"Discover includes productivity apps as well as games; many games are "
"available directly through Discover, plus emulators and game "
"downloaders/launchers like <a "
"href=\"appstream://com.valvesoftware.Steam\">Steam</a> and <a "
"href=\"appstream://com.heroicgameslauncher.hgl\">Heroic Games Launcher</a>, "
"which can be used to get even more games."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/apps-and-games.md:20 content/docs/updates.md:22
msgid "Command-line"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/apps-and-games.md:21
msgid ""
"The <code>flatpak</code> command-line tool can be run in a terminal window "
"to interact with the world of Flatpak apps. Here are some examples of basic "
"usage:"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/apps-and-games.md:23
msgid ""
"To search for apps to install, run <code>flatpak search [search "
"term]</code>."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/apps-and-games.md:24
msgid ""
"To install an app, run <code>flatpak install [id of the app you want to "
"install, expressed in reverse-dns format, e.g. org.kde.kstars]</code>."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/apps-and-games.md:25
msgid "To see what’s installed, run <code>flatpak list</code>."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/apps-and-games.md:26
msgid ""
"To uninstall an app, run <code>flatpak uninstall [id of the app you want to "
"remove, expressed in reverse-dns format, e.g. org.kde.kstars]</code>."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/apps-and-games.md:28
msgid "To learn more, run <code>flatpak --help</code>."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/apps-and-games.md:31
msgid "I can’t find something there that I know exists!"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/apps-and-games.md:32
msgid ""
"It’s probably not packaged as a Flatpak yet. What a shame! Consider "
"contacting the software’s authors and asking them to package it as a Flatpak"
" on Flathub."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/apps-and-games.md:34
msgid ""
"In the meantime, see [this page](more-software) for some options regarding "
"what to do next."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/automount.md:0
msgid "Auto-Mount Internal Disks"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/automount.md:11
msgid ""
"If your computer includes multiple internal disks, only the one containing "
"the boot volume will be automatically mounted at login. It can be useful to "
"auto-mount other ones, too. Here’s how to do so:"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/automount.md:13
msgid "Launch the _System Settings_ app"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/automount.md:14
msgid "In the sidebar list, click “Disks & Cameras”"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/automount.md:15
msgid "In the new sidebar list, click “Device Auto-mount”"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/automount.md:16
msgid ""
"In the main view, click the checkbox for “On Login” on the row of each disk "
"you want to auto-mount"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/automount.md:17
msgid "Click “Apply”"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/background.md:0
msgid "History & Architecture"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/background.md:13
msgid ""
"Veteran KDE developer Harald Sitter began working on KDE Linux in early "
"2023, and revealed its working prototype at Akademy 2024 "
"([slides](https://conf.kde.org/event/6/contributions/202/attachments/135/171/The%20Operating%20System.pdf),"
" [recording](http://www.youtube.com/live/gTxRaBEUe-I?t=25936))."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/background.md:15
msgid ""
"An [alpha release](https://pointieststick.com/2025/09/06/announcing-the-"
"alpha-release-of-kde-linux/) followed at Akademy 2025 "
"([slides](https://conf.kde.org/event/9/contributions/265/attachments/171/220/growth.pdf),"
" [recording](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=PA03J1CAYoA))."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/background.md:17
msgid ""
"The project incorporates lessons learned from the earlier [KDE "
"neon](https://neon.kde.org/) project, and focuses on resilience, modern "
"technical infrastructure, and low maintenance needs. KDE Linux’s design is "
"heavily inspired by systemd creator Lennart Poettering’s thoughts on [OS "
"design](https://0pointer.net/blog/fitting-everything-together.html) and "
"[system extensions](https://0pointer.net/blog/testing-my-system-code-in-usr-"
"without-modifying-usr.html)."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/backup.md:0
msgid "Back Up Data"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/backup.md:11
msgid ""
"KDE Linux includes a built-in system to back up your important data to a "
"secondary disk or a network location."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/backup.md:13
msgid "To set this up, do the following:"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/backup.md:15
msgid ""
"Open the *System Settings* app and click on *Backups*, at the bottom of the "
"sidebar’s *System* group."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/backup.md:16
msgid "Click *Add New Plan…*"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/backup.md:17
msgid ""
"Click *Destination* and choose where to store the backup. There are two "
"options:"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/backup.md:18
msgid ""
"**External storage disk:** plug it in, click *Mount and Open* in the popup "
"that appears, click *External Storage* on the backup destination page, and "
"select the disk in the list."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/backup.md:19
msgid ""
"**Network location:** make sure it’s manually mounted using `/etc/fstab` and"
" then select it in *Destination Path for Backup:*"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/backup.md:20
msgid "Click *Schedule* and choose a schedule."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/backup.md:21
msgid "Click *Apply*."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/backup.md:23
msgid ""
"Thereafter, your data will be periodically saved to the configured location."
" This system will keep multiple old versions of the data until the location "
"fills up, and then remove the oldest versions."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/boot-failure-recovery.md:0
msgid "Recover from Boot Failures"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/boot-failure-recovery.md:11
msgid ""
"It can be quite distressing when a computer fails to boot up normally! Here "
"are some recovery mechanisms:"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/boot-failure-recovery.md:14
msgid "Roll back to an older version of the operating system (OS)"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/boot-failure-recovery.md:15
msgid ""
"If the boot failure started happening after you updated the system, rolling "
"back to the older version will generally fix it."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/boot-failure-recovery.md:17
#: content/docs/char-input.md:69
msgid "To do this:"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/boot-failure-recovery.md:18
#: content/docs/boot-failure-recovery.md:35
msgid "Power on or restart the machine."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/boot-failure-recovery.md:19
#: content/docs/boot-failure-recovery.md:36
msgid ""
"Hold down <kbd>Space</kbd> until the OS version chooser appears (in white "
"text in the center of the screen, against a black background)."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/boot-failure-recovery.md:20
msgid ""
"Press the down arrow key once to select the prior OS version, or a different"
" one."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/boot-failure-recovery.md:21
msgid "Press <kbd>Enter</kbd> to boot into it."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/boot-failure-recovery.md:23
msgid ""
"If this fixes the issue, please report it at https://invent.kde.org/kde-"
"linux/kde-linux/-/issues/, and attach the output of running <code>journalctl"
" --boot -1 --no-pager</code> in a terminal window."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/boot-failure-recovery.md:26
msgid "Boot the system in a different way by changing the kernel command line"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/boot-failure-recovery.md:27
msgid ""
"{{< section class=\"text-center warning-bubble\" >}} Be careful with the "
"options presented here! If you are not a technical expert and don’t know "
"what you’re doing, using these tools can easily make the problem even worse."
" {{< /section >}}"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/boot-failure-recovery.md:31
msgid ""
"If that does not work, you can change how the system boots by altering the "
"kernel command line parameters to achieve various debugging approaches."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/boot-failure-recovery.md:33
msgid "To edit the kernel command line:"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/boot-failure-recovery.md:37
msgid "Press the <kbd>e</kbd> key."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/boot-failure-recovery.md:38
msgid ""
"A text field with very long text in it will appear; this is the kernel "
"command line."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/boot-failure-recovery.md:41
msgid "Disable systemd extensions"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/boot-failure-recovery.md:42
msgid ""
"Add <code>systemd.mask=systemd-sysext.service</code>to the kernel command "
"line and then press <kbd>Enter</kbd>."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/boot-failure-recovery.md:44
msgid ""
"This is useful if you have any systemd extensions active, and the boot "
"failure started happening after you updated the content in any of them; this"
" could be the cause. Temporarily disabling extensions should resolve the "
"issue until you can debug what’s wrong with it."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/boot-failure-recovery.md:47
msgid ""
"If this works, after logging in, debug what’s wrong with the extension and "
"fix it. If you are unable to, disable it."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/boot-failure-recovery.md:50
msgid "Bypass issues with the login screen or Plasma"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/boot-failure-recovery.md:51
msgid ""
"Add <code>systemd.unit=multi-user.target</code> to the kernel command line "
"and then press <kbd>Enter</kbd>."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/boot-failure-recovery.md:53
msgid ""
"This is useful if the login screen or plasma are failing to start or "
"crashing in a loop; you can boot into a command-line environment that will "
"bypass both of them, within which debugging is possible."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/boot-failure-recovery.md:55
#: content/docs/boot-failure-recovery.md:65
msgid ""
"If debugging and troubleshooting determines that the problem was not caused "
"by your own actions, [open a bug report for the KDE Linux "
"team](https://invent.kde.org/kde-linux/kde-linux/-/issues/) to investigate."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/boot-failure-recovery.md:58
msgid "Enter the emergency root shell"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/boot-failure-recovery.md:59
msgid ""
"Add <code>systemd.debug_shell=on SYSTEMD_SULOGIN_FORCE=1</code> to the "
"kernel command line and press <kbd>Enter</kbd>."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/boot-failure-recovery.md:60
msgid "Wait for the screen to turn black and stay that way for a few seconds."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/boot-failure-recovery.md:61
msgid ""
"Press <kbd>Ctrl</kbd>+<kbd>Alt</kbd>+<kbd>F9</kbd> (note: on a laptop, you "
"may also have to hold down <kbd>Fn</kbd>)."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/boot-failure-recovery.md:63
msgid ""
"You are now in the *emergency root shell*. Every command you run will be "
"executed as root, so be careful."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/boot-failure-recovery.md:68
msgid "Roll back `/etc`"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/boot-failure-recovery.md:69
msgid ""
"It’s possible for `/etc` to be modified when booted into a particular build "
"in a way that makes it incompatible with older builds."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/boot-failure-recovery.md:71
msgid ""
"This can manifest as bizarre issues after rolling back the OS, such as black"
" screens or login passwords not being accepted."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/boot-failure-recovery.md:73
msgid ""
"To recover, replace the broken `/etc` with an older, working one as follows:"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/boot-failure-recovery.md:75
msgid ""
"Get a shell via either of the above methods and run the following commands:"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/boot-failure-recovery.md:76
msgid "<code>sudo mv /etc /etc.broken</code>"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/boot-failure-recovery.md:77
msgid ""
"<code>sudo btrfs subvolume snapshot $(ls -d -1 /.etc.* | tail -2 | head -1) "
"/etc</code>"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/boot-failure-recovery.md:78
msgid "<code>systemctl reboot</code>"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/boot-failure-recovery.md:80
msgid ""
"These manual steps should become unnecessary once "
"https://invent.kde.org/kde-linux/kde-linux/-/issues/505 is implemented."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/boot-failure-recovery.md:83
#: content/docs/flatpak-crashes.md:26
msgid "Further information"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/boot-failure-recovery.md:84
msgid ""
"See https://systemd.io/DEBUGGING for more debugging options. KDE Linux uses "
"systemd exclusively, so everything on that page is relevant."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/char-input.md:0
msgid "Type Emojis, Symbols, and Accented Characters"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/char-input.md:11
msgid ""
"How do you type a `€` character when your keyboard only has `$` on it? Or "
"maybe you need `è`, `é`, or `ñ`. What about a fancy `°` degree sign? And how"
" about emojis? Technically those are characters, too!"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/char-input.md:13
msgid "KDE Linux offers multiple ways:"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/char-input.md:16
msgid "KCharSelect"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/char-input.md:17
msgid "*Easy to learn, but slow to use.*"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/char-input.md:19
msgid ""
"The [*KCharSelect*](https://apps.kde.org/kcharselect/) app lets you visually"
" search and browse through the entire catalog of characters available across"
" all languages — including emojis. Once you’ve found the appropriate "
"character, you can copy it to the clipboard for pasting elsewhere."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/char-input.md:21
msgid ""
"*KCharSelect* is not pre-installed, but can be installed using the "
"*Discover* software center."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/char-input.md:23
msgid "<a href=\"appstream://org.kde.kcharselect\">Install KCharSelect now</a>"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/char-input.md:26
msgid "Emoji Picker"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/char-input.md:27
msgid "*Easy to learn and fast to use, but limited to emojis.*"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/char-input.md:29
msgid ""
"KDE Linux includes the *Emoji Picker* app which offers a more streamlined "
"emoji-picking experience compared to using *KCharSelect*. To launch it from "
"anywhere, press <kbd>Meta</kbd>+<kbd>.</kbd>."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/char-input.md:31
msgid ""
"From there, you can search or browse for an emoji, and click on it to copy "
"it to the clipboard for pasting elsewhere. *Emoji Picker* automatically "
"remembers the last emojis you used, too."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/char-input.md:34
msgid "On-demand character palette"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/char-input.md:35
msgid ""
"*Easy to learn and fast to use, but only has partial coverage for symbols, "
"and no emojis.*"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/char-input.md:37 content/docs/char-input.md:70
msgid "Open *System Settings*"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/char-input.md:38
msgid "Navigate to *Keyboard* > *Virtual Keyboard*"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/char-input.md:39
msgid "Click *Plasma Keyboard* and click *Apply*"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/char-input.md:41
msgid ""
"Now, whenever you’d like to type an accented character, press and hold the "
"key on your physical keyboard that looks closest to it."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/char-input.md:43
msgid "For example, if you want `é`, press and hold the <kbd>e</kbd> key."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/char-input.md:45
msgid ""
"In a moment, a pop-up will appear showing possible accented characters. "
"Select the one you want by clicking on it, pressing the number key below it,"
" or navigating to it using the arrow keys and pressing <kbd>Enter</kbd>"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/char-input.md:48
msgid "Compose Key"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/char-input.md:49
msgid "*Very fast to use, but requires some learning, and no emojis.*"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/char-input.md:51
msgid ""
"See how the Euro symbol (`€`) looks kind of like the letter C with an equals"
" sign through it?"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/char-input.md:53
msgid ""
"To type `€` directly, press the <kbd>Compose</kbd> key, then <kbd>C</kbd>, "
"then <kbd>=</kbd>."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/char-input.md:55
msgid "Easy!"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/char-input.md:57
msgid ""
"Similarly, to get `é`, press <kbd>Compose</kbd>, then <kbd>e</kbd>, then "
"<kbd>'</kbd>."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/char-input.md:59
msgid "`ñ` is made with <kbd>Compose</kbd>, <kbd>n</kbd>, <kbd>~</kbd>."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/char-input.md:61
msgid "`°` is made with <kbd>Compose</kbd>, <kbd>o</kbd>, <kbd>o</kbd>"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/char-input.md:63
msgid "`…` is made with <kbd>Compose</kbd>, <kbd>.</kbd>, <kbd>.</kbd>"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/char-input.md:65
msgid "…And so on."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/char-input.md:67
msgid ""
"But which key is the <kbd>Compose</kbd> key? Your keyboard probably doesn’t "
"have one. In this case, you’ll need to re-bind an existing key you rarely or"
" never use to act as a <kbd>Compose</kbd> key."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/char-input.md:71
msgid "Click *Keyboard* in the sidebar"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/char-input.md:72
msgid "Click *Key Bindings* in the window header"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/char-input.md:73
msgid "Scroll down to where it says *Position of Compose Key* and click on it"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/char-input.md:74
msgid ""
"Choose a key to be your new <kbd>Compose</kbd> key! Some keys that are good "
"candidates because they are otherwise rarely used are <kbd>Caps Lock</kbd>, "
"<kbd>Insert</kbd>, <kbd>Pause</kbd>, and <kbd>Scroll Lock</kbd>."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/char-input.md:76
msgid ""
"Compose key sequences are generally intuitive, but to see the full list of "
"options, open a terminal window and run:"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/char-input.md:78
msgid ""
"<code>rg Multi_key /usr/share/X11/locale/en_US.UTF-8/Compose | cut -d "
"\"\\\\\"\" -f 1,2</code>"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/cjkv-input.md:0
msgid "Type in Chinese, Japanese, Korean, or Vietnamese"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/cjkv-input.md:11
msgid ""
"Typing in Chinese, Japanese, Korean, and Vietnamese requires the use of an "
"“input method” that translates physical key-presses into the right "
"characters on the screen. This page describes how to set up the popular "
"“Fcitx 5” input method and use it."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/cjkv-input.md:15
msgid ""
"First, <a href=\"appstream://org.fcitx.Fcitx5\">install Fcitx 5 using "
"*Discover*</a>."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/cjkv-input.md:17
msgid ""
"While on that the page for Fcitx5 in *Discover*, Click the *Add-Ons* button "
"in the toolbar, and install the required add-on for the language you want to"
" use. For example:"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/cjkv-input.md:18
msgid ""
"<a href=\"appstream://org.fcitx.Fcitx5.Addon.ChineseAddons\">Chinese "
"(Pinyin, Wubi, and others)</a>"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/cjkv-input.md:19
msgid ""
"<a href=\"appstream://org.fcitx.Fcitx5.Addon.Chewing\">Chinese (Zhuyin)</a>"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/cjkv-input.md:20
msgid ""
"<a href=\"appstream://org.fcitx.Fcitx5.Addon.McBopomofo\">Chinese "
"(Bopomofo)</a>"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/cjkv-input.md:21
msgid "<a href=\"appstream://org.fcitx.Fcitx5.Addon.Mozc\">Japanese</a>"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/cjkv-input.md:22
msgid "<a href=\"appstream://org.fcitx.Fcitx5.Addon.Hangul\">Korean</a>"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/cjkv-input.md:23
msgid "<a href=\"appstream://org.fcitx.Fcitx5.Addon.Unikey\">Vietnamese</a>"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/cjkv-input.md:26
msgid "Configuration"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/cjkv-input.md:27
msgid ""
"Launch *System Settings*. Navigate to *Keyboard* > *Virtual Keyboard* > "
"click “Fcitx 5” > click *Apply*."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/cjkv-input.md:29
msgid ""
"At this point, a keyboard icon has appeared in the *System Tray*. Right-"
"click it, and then click *Input Method Settings*."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/cjkv-input.md:31
msgid ""
"In the window that appears, select the input method plug-in for the desired "
"language, plus a matching keyboard layout. After selecting each one, click "
"the arrow pointing towards the list on the left to move the selected option "
"into that list."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/cjkv-input.md:33
msgid ""
"For **Chinese**, add “Keyboard - Chinese” first, then add any of the options"
" listed under “Chinese (China)” or Chinese (Taiwan)”."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/cjkv-input.md:34
msgid "For **Japanese**, add “Keyboard - Japanese” first, then add “Mozc”."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/cjkv-input.md:35
msgid "For **Korean**, add “Keyboard - Korean” first, then add “Hangul”."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/cjkv-input.md:36
msgid ""
"For **Vietnamese**, add “Keyboard - Vietnamese” first, then add “Unikey”."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/cjkv-input.md:38
msgid ""
"If you are prompted to change your system layout to match the input method, "
"click *Yes*."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/cjkv-input.md:41 content/docs/kde-dev.md:30
msgid "Use"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/cjkv-input.md:42
msgid "Type as expected."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/cjkv-input.md:44
msgid ""
"To type Latin characters instead of using the input method and, press "
"<kbd>Ctrl</kbd>+<kbd>Space</kbd> while a text field is focused, or click the"
" symbol for the active input method in the *System Tray*. Do the same thing "
"a second time to return to using the input method."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/dev.md:0
msgid "Develop Software"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/dev.md:11
msgid ""
"Common build tools are pre-installed, so the hard part here is usually "
"getting the software’s dependencies, since KDE Linux doesn’t include a "
"package manager you can use to install them."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/dev.md:13
msgid ""
"[Using Distrobox](../more-software/#distrobox) is currently the preferred "
"option: follow the build instructions for the project itself using a "
"Distrobox container for the project’s best-supported Linux distro."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/dev.md:15
msgid ""
"If the software you’re compiling needs to be installed systemwide, [set up a"
" systemd extension (sysext) to hold it](../override-usr)."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/dev.md:18 content/docs/nix.md:151 content/docs/override-usr.md:45
msgid "See also"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/dev.md:19
msgid "[Install software not available in Discover](../more-software)"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/flatpak-crashes.md:0
msgid "Debug Crashes in Flatpak Apps"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/flatpak-crashes.md:11
msgid ""
"First install debug packages for the app that crashed. Run the following "
"command in a terminal window:"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/flatpak-crashes.md:12
msgid ""
"<pre>\n"
"flatpak install --include-sdk --include-debug [app id]\n"
"</pre>\n"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/flatpak-crashes.md:16
msgid ""
"Where <code>[app id]</code> is the ID of the app, like "
"<code>org.kde.okular</code>."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/flatpak-crashes.md:18
msgid "Then get a backtrace of the crash:"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/flatpak-crashes.md:19
msgid ""
"<pre>\n"
"flatpak-coredumpctl [app id]\n"
"</pre>\n"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/flatpak-crashes.md:23
msgid ""
"Then follow the [normal instructions for using "
"<code>coredumpctl</code>](https://community.kde.org/Guidelines_and_HOWTOs/Debugging/How_to_create_useful_crash_reports#Retrieving_a_backtrace_using_coredumpctl)"
" to complete the process of getting a developer-readable backtrace of the "
"crash."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/flatpak-crashes.md:27
msgid "https://docs.flatpak.org/en/latest/debugging.html"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/fonts.md:0
msgid "Install New fonts"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/fonts.md:11
msgid ""
"KDE Linux includes an intentionally minimal set of fonts. Follow either of "
"the following approaches to get more:"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/fonts.md:13
msgid "From System Settings"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/fonts.md:14
msgid "Easiest, but with a limited set of available fonts."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/fonts.md:16
msgid ""
"Open *System Settings* and navigate to *Text & Fonts* > *Font Management*."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/fonts.md:17
msgid "Click the *Get New Fonts…* button."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/fonts.md:18
msgid ""
"Locate the desired fonts in the dialog window that appears and click on "
"their *Install* buttons."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/fonts.md:20
msgid "Manually"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/fonts.md:21
msgid "More work, but supports almost any font you can find."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/fonts.md:23
msgid ""
"Acquire the font files from any sources. Websites, a local administrator, "
"etc."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/fonts.md:24
msgid "Locate the font files and double-click them."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/fonts.md:25
msgid ""
"When prompted for a location to install them, choose *User*. KDE Linux does "
"not support systemwide font installation right now."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/fstab.md:0
msgid "Why is /etc/fstab Empty?"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/fstab.md:11
msgid ""
"KDE Linux uses systemd to automatically mount system disks and partitions, "
"so the classic `/etc/fstab` file isn’t needed."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/fstab.md:13
msgid ""
"To automatically mount a non-system disk or partition, use [Plasma’s auto-"
"mount system](automount)."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/fstab.md:15
msgid ""
"To access network shares, [navigate to them using *Dolphin* and then "
"bookmark them](network-shares)."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/governance.md:0
msgid "Governance"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/governance.md:13
msgid "Leadership"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/governance.md:14
msgid ""
"KDE Linux follows a \"council of elders\" model with the council comprising "
"the project’s top contributors across the fields of:"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/governance.md:15
msgid "Founding the project"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/governance.md:16
msgid "Doing development work on the project"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/governance.md:17
msgid "Maintaining the infrastructure for the project"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/governance.md:18
msgid "Presenting about the project in public and blogging about it"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/governance.md:19
msgid "Writing documentation about the project"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/governance.md:20
msgid "Doing user support and outreach for the project"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/governance.md:21
msgid "Contributing bananas to fellow KDE community members"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/governance.md:23
msgid ""
"This being necessarily difficult to quantify, the council currently consists"
" of:"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/governance.md:24
msgid "[Harald Sitter](https://invent.kde.org/sitter)"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/governance.md:25
msgid "[Nate Graham](https://invent.kde.org/ngraham)"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/governance.md:26
msgid "[Lasath Fernando](https://invent.kde.org/fernando)"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/governance.md:27
msgid "[Hadi Chokr](https://invent.kde.org/silverhadch)"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/governance.md:28
msgid "[Thomas Duckworth](https://invent.kde.org/tduck)"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/governance.md:31
msgid "Decision-making"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/governance.md:32
msgid "Consensus governance is strongly encouraged and preferred."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/governance.md:34
msgid ""
"Non-trivial changes should be proposed in the form of merge requests that "
"get approved by someone on the council of elders. Pushing directly to master"
" is discouraged."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/governance.md:36
msgid ""
"Large topics are discussed in monthly calls. History and conclusions/adopted"
" policies based on discussions in these calls can be found at "
"https://community.kde.org/KDE_Linux/Calls"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/governance.md:39
msgid "Voting"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/governance.md:40
msgid ""
"In the event of yes/no disagreements among the council members, the matter "
"may be settled by majority vote, with the \\#1 council member breaking ties."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/governance.md:42
msgid ""
"Votes take the form of [work items in the KDE Linux "
"repo](https://invent.kde.org/kde-linux/kde-linux/-/work_items) that describe"
" the matter being voted on. Only council members being may vote. A vote ends"
" when all council members have voted, or after 4 days have elapsed — "
"whichever comes first. Decisions made in this way can only be changed later "
"by unanimous consent of all council members, or by another vote a minimum of"
" 6 months after the last one."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/install-vm.md:0
msgid "Install in a Virtual Machine"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/install-vm.md:13
msgid ""
"KDE Linux ships a regular bootable `.iso` image, so you can install it in a "
"virtual machine the same way as any other Linux distribution — create a VM, "
"attach the ISO, boot, run the installer, then reboot from the installed "
"disk."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/install-vm.md:15
msgid ""
"The only KDE-Linux-specific requirement is **UEFI firmware**: the VM must be"
" set to UEFI rather than legacy BIOS, or the image will not boot. If it "
"still refuses to boot, disable Secure Boot."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/install-vm.md:17
msgid ""
"Each VM app puts the UEFI setting in a different place — here's where to "
"find it:"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/install-vm.md:20
msgid "Oracle VirtualBox"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/install-vm.md:22
msgid ""
"In the wizard check the checkbox labeled *Enable EFI* when setting up the VM"
" Hardware. (Or, from a terminal after the fact, run: `VBoxManage modifyvm "
"\"<vm-name>\" --firmware efi`.)"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/install-vm.md:25
msgid "Virtual Machine Manager (virt-manager)"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/install-vm.md:27
msgid ""
"On the last page of the wizard, check the checkbox labeled *Customize "
"configuration before install*, then set *Overview > Firmware* to *UEFI* "
"before clicking *Begin Installation*."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/install-vm.md:30
msgid "QEMU"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/install-vm.md:32
msgid ""
"There is no wizard; you enable UEFI by pointing QEMU at OVMF firmware. Make "
"a writable copy of the variables store and pass both pflash drives:"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/install-vm.md:34
msgid ""
"<pre>\n"
"cp /usr/share/edk2/x64/OVMF_VARS.4m.fd ./OVMF_VARS.4m.fd\n"
"qemu-img create -f qcow2 kde-linux.qcow2 20G\n"
"\n"
"qemu-system-x86_64 -enable-kvm -m 4G -smp 4 \\\n"
"  -drive if=pflash,format=raw,readonly=on,file=/usr/share/edk2/x64/OVMF_CODE.4m.fd \\\n"
"  -drive if=pflash,format=raw,file=./OVMF_VARS.4m.fd \\\n"
"  -drive file=kde-linux.qcow2,if=virtio \\\n"
"  -cdrom kde-linux.iso\n"
"</pre>\n"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/install-vm.md:45
msgid ""
"Drop the `-cdrom` line once the install is finished to boot from the disk. "
"The OVMF path differs by host distro: Arch's `edk2-ovmf` package puts the "
"files in `/usr/share/edk2/x64/`, while Debian/Ubuntu use `/usr/share/OVMF/`."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/install-vm.md:48
msgid "XCP-ng"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/install-vm.md:50
msgid ""
"Set the VM *Template* to *Generic Linux UEFI* when creating it. That is the "
"UEFI toggle."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/install-vm.md:53
msgid "UTM (macOS)"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/install-vm.md:55
msgid ""
"Choose *Emulate*, **not** *Virtualize* — Apple's Virtualization framework is"
" incompatible with the KDE Linux image. UTM's emulated Linux profile boots "
"via UEFI by default; if it does not boot, check that *UEFI Boot* is enabled "
"in the VM's QEMU settings."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/install.md:0
msgid "Install KDE Linux"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/install.md:13
msgid ""
"{{< section class=\"text-center warning-bubble\" >}} Currently the Testing "
"edition is available, showcasing the latest and greatest in-development "
"versions of KDE’s [Plasma desktop environment](https://kde.org/plasma-"
"desktop) and [apps](https://apps.kde.org). <br/><br/> Expect frequent "
"changes and regressions, and use it in a production environment at your own "
"risk! <br/><br/> Other editions suitable for the general public are in "
"progress. {{< /section >}}"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/install.md:21
msgid "&nbsp;"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/install.md:23
msgid ""
"Looking for instructions for installing KDE Linux in a virtual machine? "
"[Find them here.](install-vm)"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/install.md:26
msgid "Requirements"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/install.md:27
msgid "KDE Linux supports almost all PC desktops and laptops with:"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/install.md:28
msgid "UEFI firmware (this includes most sold in the last 15 years)"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/install.md:29
msgid "An AMD or Intel CPU"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/install.md:30
msgid "2 GB of memory"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/install.md:31
msgid "15 GB of storage space"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/install.md:34
msgid "Known hardware limitations"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/install.md:35
msgid ""
"**ARM-based CPUs:** e.g. Apple “M”-series CPUs and Qualcomm Snapdragon CPUs:"
" not supported yet."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/install.md:36
msgid ""
"**NVIDIA graphics cards**: cards from the “Turing” series or later (e.g. GTX"
" 1630 or newer) work out of the box. Older cards are limited to the "
"“Nouveau” driver, which [requires manual setup](pre-turing-nvidia/) ([learn "
"more](/nvidia))."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/install.md:37
msgid ""
"**Broadcom wireless cards**: [cards listed "
"here](https://wireless.docs.kernel.org/en/latest/en/users/drivers/brcm80211.html#supported-"
"chips) are supported out of the box. Other cards are not supported."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/install.md:38
msgid "**DisplayLink screens:** not supported. Display*Port* works fine."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/install.md:39
msgid ""
"**Printers:** Most modern “driverless” and wireless printers made in the "
"last 10 years or so — including [all listed "
"here](https://openprinting.github.io/printers/) — will work out of the box. "
"Drivers are included for many older wired printers, but not all. See the "
"list of [known incompatible printers here](https://invent.kde.org/kde-"
"linux/kde-"
"linux/-/issues/?sort=created_date&state=opened&label_name[]=Hardware%20compatibility&label_name[]=Printers%20🔨)."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/install.md:42
msgid "Known software issues"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/install.md:43
msgid ""
"See the items on the [list of significant limitations and known "
"issues](https://invent.kde.org/groups/kde-"
"linux/-/issues?sort=created_date&state=opened&label_name%5B%5D=Significant%20user-"
"facing%20issue&not%5Blabel_name%5D%5B%5D=Hardware%20compatibility&first_page_size=100)."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/install.md:45
msgid ""
"Ultimately the best way to determine KDE Linux’s suitability for your needs "
"and hardware is to create a live USB drive and preview it on your own "
"computer, with no risk to what’s already on it."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/install.md:48
msgid "1. Create a live USB drive"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/install.md:49
msgid ""
"Download the latest `.iso` image from [here](https://files.kde.org/kde-"
"linux/?C=M;O=D)."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/install.md:50
msgid ""
"Verify that the `.iso` file is genuine: visit https://files.kde.org/kde-"
"linux/?C=M;O=D and click *Details* for the .iso file you downloaded. Copy "
"the long string of nonsense characters next to *SHA256* to the clipboard. "
"Right-click on the downloaded `.iso` file on your computer, choose "
"*Properties*, and then click on the *Checksums* tab. Paste the checksum from"
" the website into the text field and press the `enter` key. Wait for the "
"text field at the top to turn green. If it does, the file on your computer "
"is the same one that you downloaded. If not, the file may be corrupt; try "
"the download again."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/install.md:51
msgid ""
"If the file is genuine, install [ISO Image "
"Writer](https://apps.kde.org/isoimagewriter/) and launch it."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/install.md:52
msgid "Click “Path to ISO Image…” and locate the `.iso` file you downloaded."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/install.md:53
msgid ""
"Plug in the USB flash drive and ensure it appears in the “To this USB Drive”"
" area."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/install.md:54
msgid "Click “Create”."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/install.md:57
msgid "2. Prepare the target computer"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/install.md:58
msgid ""
"Ensure that Secure Boot is disabled. If it isn’t, or you don’t know whether "
"it is or not, enter the computer’s UEFI interface and disable it. Here’s "
"how:"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/install.md:60
msgid ""
"First, consult [the table "
"here](https://forums.malwarebytes.com/topic/319165-pc-common-boot-menu-and-"
"bios-setting-hotkeys/) and find the correct keyboard key under the "
"“BIOS/UEFI Key” column for your brand of computer."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/install.md:61
msgid ""
"To enter the UEFI interface, reboot the computer and repeatedly press that "
"key while it starts up."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/install.md:62
msgid ""
"Once you’re in the UEFI interface (you’ll know because it looks very ugly), "
"find where it lets you turn off Secure Boot and turn it off. This is "
"different for every UEFI implementation, so you may need to dig around a "
"bit."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/install.md:63
msgid ""
"Once you’ve turned off Secure Boot, find the “Exit and save changes” option,"
" and use it."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/install.md:65
msgid ""
"This requirement will go away in the future once [KDE Linux supports Secure "
"Boot](https://invent.kde.org/kde-linux/kde-linux/-/issues/3)."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/install.md:68
msgid "3. Boot into the live USB drive"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/install.md:69
msgid "Plug in the USB drive."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/install.md:70
msgid ""
"Consult [the table here](https://forums.malwarebytes.com/topic/319165-pc-"
"common-boot-menu-and-bios-setting-hotkeys/) and note down the keyboard key "
"under the “Boot Menu Key” column for your brand of computer."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/install.md:71
msgid "Reboot the computer and repeatedly press that key while it starts up."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/install.md:72
msgid ""
"When the boot menu appears, use the Up or Down arrow keys to select the "
"entry that looks like it describes your USB flash drive, and then press "
"Enter."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/install.md:75
msgid "4. Explore the live session and install KDE Linux"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/install.md:76
msgid ""
"Now you’re in the “Live Session” of KDE Linux! This lets you see what it "
"will be like if you choose to install it. Go through the welcome wizard and "
"then poke around to make sure everything you care about works. Plug in your "
"typically-used devices and make sure they function properly."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/install.md:78
msgid ""
"Once you’re ready to install, double-click on the “Install KDE Linux” icon "
"on the desktop and go through the installer. Installing KDE Linux to the "
"entire disk (erasing all existing data) is the most reliable option. Other "
"installation methods may work, but are known to [fail under certain "
"circumstances](https://invent.kde.org/kde-linux/kde-"
"linux/-/work_items?label_name%5B%5D=Live%20session%2Finstaller) and are "
"therefore **not recommended**."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/install.md:80
msgid ""
"WARNING: if you choose to erase the computer’s hard disk, all of the files "
"and data on it will be erased too. Make sure anything you care about is "
"backed up somewhere!"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/install.md:83
msgid "5. Enjoy KDE Linux"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/install.md:84
msgid "We hope you love it!"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/kde-dev.md:0
msgid "Develop KDE Software"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/kde-dev.md:11
msgid ""
"KDE Linux is an excellent development platform for KDE software. There are "
"three primary paths, depending on how the KDE software you want to develop "
"is shipped on KDE Linux:"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/kde-dev.md:12
msgid ""
"[Developing KDE software that’s shipped on the base image](#build-kde-"
"software-thats-shipped-on-the-base-image)"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/kde-dev.md:13
msgid ""
"[Developing KDE software that can be built using Flatpak](#build-kde-app-"
"with-a-flatpak-manifest)"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/kde-dev.md:14
msgid ""
"[Developing any KDE software using Distrobox](#build-any-kde-software-using-"
"kde-builder-in-distrobox)"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/kde-dev.md:18
msgid "Build KDE software that’s shipped on the base image"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/kde-dev.md:19
msgid ""
"This workflow is used for developing KDE software that’s shipped on the base"
" system, or even Qt. A list of such software [can be found "
"here](https://invent.kde.org/kde-linux/kde-linux-"
"packages/-/blob/master/targets.yaml) (note that “workspace” includes Plasma,"
" KWin, and Plasma-aligned apps such as System Settings and Discover)."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/kde-dev.md:21
msgid ""
"The best way to do this is by using <code>systemd-sysext</code>, which "
"allows overlaying built-from-source content on top of <code>/usr/</code> "
"without impacting the base system."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/kde-dev.md:23 content/docs/kde-dev.md:61
msgid "Setup"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/kde-dev.md:24
msgid "Run the setup script:"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/kde-dev.md:26
msgid ""
"<pre>\n"
"set-up-system-development\n"
"</pre>\n"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/kde-dev.md:31
msgid ""
"In a nutshell, you’ll compile and install software using <code>kde-"
"builder</code>, then refresh the systemd extension, and then finally restart"
" any services that you changed (e.g. Plasma), or the entire system."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/kde-dev.md:33
msgid ""
"For example, to compile and test a change to plasma-pa, do the following:"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/kde-dev.md:35
msgid ""
"<pre>\n"
"kde-builder plasma-pa\n"
"sudo systemd-sysext refresh --always-refresh=yes\n"
"systemctl restart --user plasma-plasmashell.service\n"
"</pre>\n"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/kde-dev.md:41
msgid ""
"If you replace a core system component and find that everything is crashing "
"after the refresh is applied, try rebooting in order to fully reload the new"
" dependency in all running software."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/kde-dev.md:43
msgid ""
"When you’re finished developing or testing the change, disable (“un-merge”) "
"the system extension:"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/kde-dev.md:45 content/docs/override-usr.md:40
msgid ""
"<pre>\n"
"sudo systemd-sysext unmerge\n"
"</pre>\n"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/kde-dev.md:49
msgid ""
"When you’re done with your built-from-source software (e.g. because it was "
"accepted as a patch and merged), delete the installed files:"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/kde-dev.md:51
msgid ""
"<pre>\n"
"rm -r ~/kde/usr/*\n"
"# When you’re prompted to delete the read-only extension-release.kde file, answer 'n'\n"
"</pre>\n"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/kde-dev.md:56
msgid "Build KDE app with a Flatpak manifest"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/kde-dev.md:57
msgid ""
"To develop or test changes to the app code itself, build the app using "
"<code>flatpak-builder</code>, so that the result is functionally identical "
"to the app’s nightly Flatpak build."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/kde-dev.md:59
msgid ""
"To develop or test changes to a KDE Framework or other library used by "
"multiple apps, the only relatively painless approach at the moment is to use"
" <code>kde-builder</code> to build them all. See [Developing KDE software "
"that’s shipped on the base image](#build-kde-software-thats-shipped-on-the-"
"base-image)."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/kde-dev.md:62
msgid ""
"flatpak-builder will install flatpak packages from the remote flathub-apps-"
"built-locally. This remote is the official Flathub store."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/kde-dev.md:64
msgid ""
"<pre>\n"
"flatpak remote-add --user --if-not-exists flathub-apps-built-locally https://flathub.org/repo/flathub.flatpakrepo\n"
"</pre>\n"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/kde-dev.md:68
msgid "Make changes to just the app"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/kde-dev.md:69
msgid ""
"First check out the source code for the KDE app you’d like to build. For "
"example, here with Filelight:"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/kde-dev.md:71
msgid ""
"<pre>\n"
"# Create folder to hold KDE source code. Skippable if it already exists\n"
"mkdir -p ~/kde/src/\n"
"\n"
"# Go into that folder\n"
"cd ~/kde/src/\n"
"\n"
"# Download source code for Filelight\n"
"git clone git@invent.kde.org:utilities/filelight.git\n"
"\n"
"# Go into Filelight’s source code folder\n"
"cd ~/kde/src/filelight\n"
"\n"
"# Build Filelight as a flatpak\n"
"flatpak-builder build --user --install-deps-from=flathub-apps-built-locally --force-clean --ccache --install .flatpak-manifest.json\n"
"</pre>\n"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/kde-dev.md:88
msgid ""
"<code>flatpak-builder</code> will create a flatpak repo and remote named "
"<code>filelight-origin</code> and export the freshly built Filelight flatpak"
" to this flatpak repo."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/kde-dev.md:90
msgid "Now run it:"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/kde-dev.md:92
msgid ""
"<pre>\n"
"org.kde.filelight\n"
"</pre>\n"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/kde-dev.md:96
msgid "For further information, see:"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/kde-dev.md:97
msgid "https://docs.flatpak.org/en/latest/getting-started.html"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/kde-dev.md:98
msgid "https://develop.kde.org/docs/packaging/flatpak/packaging/"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/kde-dev.md:101
msgid "Build any KDE software, using KDE Builder in Distrobox"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/kde-dev.md:102
msgid ""
"If you need to work on some KDE software not preinstalled on the base system"
" (so dependencies are also not pre-installed) that also does not or cannot "
"build as a Flatpak, you can build it with <code>kde-builder</code> in a "
"Distrobox:"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/kde-dev.md:104
msgid ""
"<pre>\n"
"# As per https://develop.kde.org/docs/getting-started/building/containers-distrobox\n"
"distrobox create --image docker.io/archlinux --name kdebuildercontainer --home ~/kdebuildercontainer_home\n"
"distrobox enter kdebuildercontainer\n"
"sudo pacman -Syu\n"
"sudo pacman -S nano\n"
"echo 'export PATH=\"$HOME/.local/bin:$PATH\"' | tee --append ~/.{bash,zsh}rc\n"
"exit\n"
"distrobox enter kdebuildercontainer\n"
"\n"
"# Install kde-builder as usual. https://develop.kde.org/docs/getting-started/building/kde-builder-setup\n"
"</pre>\n"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/kde-linux-dev.md:0
msgid "Help Develop KDE Linux"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/kde-linux-dev.md:12
msgid ""
"The KDE Linux team always appreciates help developing KDE Linux into the "
"operating system of the future!"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/kde-linux-dev.md:14
msgid ""
"**To talk with the KDE Linux developers**, [use "
"Matrix](https://matrix.to/#/%23kde-linux:kde.org)."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/kde-linux-dev.md:15
msgid ""
"**To propose changes**, submit a Merge Request in [one of the relevant git "
"repositories](https://invent.kde.org/kde-linux/)."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/kde-linux-dev.md:16
msgid ""
"**To report issues in the KDE Linux operating system itself** (i.e. OS "
"design, integration, system services, etc), [use "
"invent.kde.org](https://invent.kde.org/kde-linux/kde-linux/-/issues/new), "
"and ignore the scary red banner at the top of the page."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/kde-linux-dev.md:17 content/help.md:19
msgid ""
"**To report issues in KDE Plasma or any KDE apps**, [use "
"bugs.kde.org](https://bugs.kde.org/)."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/kde-linux-dev.md:18
msgid ""
"**To get help with something related to KDE Linux**, [use "
"discuss.kde.org](https://discuss.kde.org/), and tag your post with “kde-"
"linux”."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/kde-linux-dev.md:21
msgid "CI Images"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/kde-linux-dev.md:22
msgid ""
"Check the build log for your pipeline. It should mention where the images "
"have been published."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/kde-linux-dev.md:24
msgid ""
"You can also browse the images [from "
"here](https://qoomon.github.io/aws-s3-bucket-"
"browser/index.html?bucket=https://storage.kde.org/ci-artifacts/#kde-"
"linux/kde-linux/)."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/kde-linux-dev.md:27
msgid "Improve Local Build Speed"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/kde-linux-dev.md:28
msgid ""
"In order to speed up local builds, create a <code>mkosi.local.conf</code> "
"file in the root of the repository with the following content:"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/kde-linux-dev.md:30
msgid ""
"<pre>\n"
"[Content]\n"
"Environment=LOCALE_GEN=\"en_US.UTF-8 UTF-8\" # replace with your locale`\n"
"Environment=MIRRORS_COUNTRY=us # replace with your country code`\n"
"Environment=PARALLEL_DOWNLOADS=50 # if your internet connection is fast\n"
"</pre>\n"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/kde-linux-dev.md:37
msgid ""
"You need to be using the Btrfs storage driver for docker, otherwise this "
"won’t really work."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/kde-linux-dev.md:39
msgid ""
"If your host filesystem uses Btrfs (like KDE Linux), add the following to "
"/etc/docker/daemon.json"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/kde-linux-dev.md:41
msgid ""
"<pre>\n"
"{\n"
"  \"storage-driver\": \"btrfs\"\n"
"}\n"
"</pre>\n"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/kde-linux-dev.md:47
msgid ""
"Official docker documentation explaining this [can be found "
"here](https://docs.docker.com/engine/storage/drivers/btrfs-"
"driver/#configure-docker-to-use-the-btrfs-storage-driver)."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/kde-linux-dev.md:49
msgid ""
"If you don’t use Btrfs for your host machine, you can still create a Btrfs "
"volume backed by a file like so:"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/kde-linux-dev.md:51
msgid ""
"<pre>\n"
"systemctl stop docker.socket docker.service || true\n"
"fallocate -l 64G /store/docker.btrfs\n"
"mkfs.btrfs /store/docker.btrfs\n"
"[ -d /var/lib/docker ] || mkdir /var/lib/docker\n"
"mount /store/docker.btrfs /var/lib/docker\n"
"systemctl restart docker.socket docker.service\n"
"</pre>\n"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/kde-linux-dev.md:60
msgid "Then run:"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/kde-linux-dev.md:62
msgid ""
"<pre>\n"
"./build_docker.sh --incremental\n"
"</pre>\n"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/kde-linux-dev.md:66
msgid "Building Custom System Images"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/kde-linux-dev.md:68
msgid ""
"You can generate custom KDE Linux images to test package integrations or "
"system modifications locally. The build process uses <code>mkosi</code> "
"wrapped in a Docker container."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/kde-linux-dev.md:70
msgid ""
"To include custom packages, add the desired package names to the relevant "
"configuration files (such as the <code>[Packages]</code> section in "
"<code>mkosi.conf</code> or the specific <code>.packages</code> files) before"
" running the build script."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/kde-linux-dev.md:72
msgid "Run the build with:"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/kde-linux-dev.md:74
msgid ""
"<pre>\n"
"./build_docker.sh\n"
"</pre>\n"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/kde-linux-dev.md:78
msgid ""
"Once the build finishes successfully, the output will be a <code>.iso</code>"
" image file located in <code>mkosi.output/</code>."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/kde-linux-dev.md:80
msgid "Quick Testing with Virt-Manager"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/kde-linux-dev.md:82
msgid ""
"The fastest way to test your changes is to boot the <code>.iso</code> image "
"directly as an existing disk in a Virtual Machine, bypassing the full "
"installation process."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/kde-linux-dev.md:84
msgid ""
"Open *Virtual Machine Manager* and start the *New Virtual Machine* wizard."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/kde-linux-dev.md:85
msgid ""
"Select *Local Install Media* and choose your generated <code>.iso</code> "
"file."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/kde-linux-dev.md:86
msgid "Allocate at least 4GB of RAM and 2 CPU cores."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/kde-linux-dev.md:87
msgid ""
"**Important:** In the VM configuration, ensure the **Firmware** is set to "
"**UEFI** and **Secure Boot** is disabled."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/kde-linux-dev.md:89
msgid ""
"For a more permanent setup or instructions on using other virtualization "
"tools like VirtualBox or UTM, refer to the [Installing in a Virtual "
"Machine](./install-vm.md) guide."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/kernel-cmdline.md:0
msgid "Set Additional Kernel Command-Line Arguments"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/kernel-cmdline.md:11
msgid ""
"At times it may be necessary to set additional command-line arguments for "
"the kernel shipped with KDE Linux, and have them persist indefinitely — for "
"example, to turn on experimental hardware or driver support, or enable "
"hardware passthrough support for virtual machines."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/kernel-cmdline.md:13
msgid ""
"{{< section class=\"text-center warning-bubble\" >}} <strong>Warning: this "
"process is dangerous</strong>. Setting inappropriate kernel command-line "
"arguments can reduce performance, increase energy usage, damage hardware "
"components, or prevent the system from starting up."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/kernel-cmdline.md:16
msgid ""
"Only proceed if you accept these risks, [have a backup](backup), and possess"
" the technical ability to reverse any mistakes. {{< /section >}}"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/kernel-cmdline.md:19
msgid "<br/>\n"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/kernel-cmdline.md:21
msgid "If you’d like to proceed, here’s how:"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/kernel-cmdline.md:23
msgid ""
"Create the folder <tt>/boot/loader/addons/</tt> (only needs to be done once "
"per system):<br/> <code>run0 mkdir -p /boot/loader/addons/</code>"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/kernel-cmdline.md:26
msgid ""
"Create a kernel add-on containing the desired command-line arguments:<br/> "
"<code>run0 ukify build --cmdline '[arguments go here]' --output "
"/boot/loader/addons/extra_args.addon.efi</code><br/> Replace "
"<code>[arguments go here]</code> with the actual command-line arguments. For"
" example: <code>debug_objects</code>"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/kernel-cmdline.md:30
msgid ""
"This add-on will then apply the additional kernel arguments for every boot, "
"irrespective of which OS version the system is booted into."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/kernel-cmdline.md:32
msgid ""
"If the add-on causes problems or is no longer needed, simply delete it:"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/kernel-cmdline.md:34
msgid "<code>run0 rm /boot/loader/addons/extra_args.addon.efi</code>"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/kernel-cmdline.md:38
msgid ""
"A full list of supported command-line options [can be found "
"here](https://www.kernel.org/doc/html/v4.14/admin-guide/kernel-"
"parameters.html)."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/kernel-dev.md:0
msgid "Develop or Debug the Kernel"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/kernel-dev.md:11
msgid "***This page is a work in progress.***"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/kernel-dev.md:13
msgid ""
"KDE Linux provides a complete, preconfigured kernel development environment "
"out of the box. No additional packages, containers, virtual machines, or "
"chroots are required. Kernel development follows standard upstream Linux "
"workflows, with a small number of integration steps specific to KDE Linux "
"explained below."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/kernel-dev.md:16
msgid "Upstream documentation"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/kernel-dev.md:17
msgid ""
"Kernel development on KDE Linux follows upstream Linux practices. Before "
"proceeding, it is strongly recommended to become familiar with the official "
"Linux kernel documentation:"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/kernel-dev.md:18
msgid "https://docs.kernel.org/"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/kernel-dev.md:19
msgid "https://docs.kernel.org/process/"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/kernel-dev.md:20
msgid "https://docs.kernel.org/kbuild/"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/kernel-dev.md:21
msgid "https://docs.kernel.org/rust/"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/kernel-dev.md:23
msgid ""
"These documents describe the development process, coding style, build "
"system, and (optionally) Rust support used by the kernel."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/kernel-dev.md:26
msgid "Prerequisites"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/kernel-dev.md:27
msgid ""
"KDE Linux uses a read-only <code>/usr</code>. filesystem. Any custom kernel,"
" kernel modules, or related artifacts must be installed via a writable "
"overlay."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/kernel-dev.md:29
msgid ""
"Before continuing, you **must** [set up a systemd system extension "
"(sysext)](../override-usr) to allow overriding content in <code>/usr</code>."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/kernel-dev.md:31
msgid ""
"This step is mandatory. All kernel images and modules built in this guide "
"are installed into the sysext and then merged into the live system."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/kernel-dev.md:34
msgid "Cloning the Linux kernel"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/kernel-dev.md:35
msgid "Clone the upstream Linux kernel repository using Git:"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/kernel-dev.md:37
msgid ""
"<pre>\n"
"git clone https://git.kernel.org/pub/scm/linux/kernel/git/torvalds/linux.git\n"
"cd linux\n"
"</pre>\n"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/kernel-dev.md:42
msgid ""
"You may also clone a specific stable or development branch if required."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/kernel-dev.md:45
msgid "Kernel configuration"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/kernel-dev.md:46
msgid "You can start from the default configuration for your architecture:"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/kernel-dev.md:48
msgid ""
"<pre>\n"
"make defconfig\n"
"</pre>\n"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/kernel-dev.md:52
msgid ""
"To customize the configuration, use one of the standard kernel configuration"
" interfaces:"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/kernel-dev.md:54
msgid ""
"<pre>\n"
"make menuconfig\n"
"make nconfig\n"
"make xconfig\n"
"</pre>\n"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/kernel-dev.md:60
msgid ""
"All configuration steps are identical to upstream Linux kernel development."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/kernel-dev.md:63
msgid "Building the kernel"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/kernel-dev.md:64
msgid "Build the kernel using the standard build system:"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/kernel-dev.md:66
msgid ""
"<pre>\n"
"make -j$(nproc)\n"
"</pre>\n"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/kernel-dev.md:70
msgid "This produces the kernel image and modules in the build tree."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/kernel-dev.md:73
msgid "Installing into the sysext"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/kernel-dev.md:74
msgid "Install the kernel modules into the sysext overlay:"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/kernel-dev.md:76
msgid ""
"<pre>\n"
"make INSTALL_MOD_PATH=\"$HOME/kde/usr\" modules_install\n"
"</pre>\n"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/kernel-dev.md:80
msgid "Determine the kernel version and install the kernel image:"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/kernel-dev.md:82
msgid ""
"<pre>\n"
"version=$(make -s kernelrelease)\n"
"install -Dm644 \"$(make -s image_name)\" \\\n"
"  \"$HOME/kde/usr/lib/modules/$version/vmlinuz\"\n"
"</pre>\n"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/kernel-dev.md:88
msgid ""
"Refresh the systemd system extension so the system sees the new kernel and "
"modules:"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/kernel-dev.md:90
msgid ""
"<pre>\n"
"run0 systemd-sysext refresh\n"
"</pre>\n"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/kernel-dev.md:95
msgid "Rebuilding EFI images"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/kernel-dev.md:96
msgid ""
"After installing the kernel into the sysext, rebuild the EFI artifacts based"
" on the updated <code>/usr</code> contents:"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/kernel-dev.md:98
msgid ""
"<pre>\n"
"run0 /usr/lib/rebuild-efi\n"
"</pre>\n"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/kernel-dev.md:102
msgid "This step generates a new Unified Kernel Image (UKI)."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/kernel-dev.md:105
msgid "Installing the Unified Kernel Image"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/kernel-dev.md:107
msgid "Install the generated UKI into the EFI System Partition:"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/kernel-dev.md:109
msgid ""
"<pre>\n"
"run0 cp kde-linux.efi /boot/EFI/Linux/\n"
"</pre>\n"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/kernel-dev.md:113
msgid ""
"The new kernel will appear as an unversioned entry in systemd-boot and can "
"be selected at the next boot."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/low-latency.md:0
msgid "Reduce Latency for Specialized Software"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/low-latency.md:11
msgid ""
"Some apps benefits from being run with very *low latency*, or low potential "
"for lag, stutter, and interruptions from other running software. Most apps "
"don’t need this — not even video games — but some do, including those for "
"professional audio production."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/low-latency.md:13
msgid ""
"In KDE Linux, apps are allowed to ask for low latency privileges themselves."
" Any that don’t can be given these privileges manually. If you encounter lag"
" or stuttering in performance-critical apps, here are some methods of doing "
"that:"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/low-latency.md:15
msgid "Give a specific app or process low latency privileges"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/low-latency.md:16
msgid ""
"Launch the app you want to apply low latency privileges to, if it’s not "
"already running."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/low-latency.md:17
msgid "Open *System Monitor*."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/low-latency.md:18
msgid "Locate the app or process on the *Applications* or *Processes* page."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/low-latency.md:19
msgid "Right-click on it and click *Set Priority…*."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/low-latency.md:20
msgid ""
"In the dialog window that appears, increase the sliders’ priority values and"
" click on the radio buttons for “FIFO” and “Real Time”."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/low-latency.md:22
msgid "Give all apps or processes low latency privileges"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/low-latency.md:23
msgid ""
"Put your user account in the `realtime` group by running <code>sudo useradd "
"-G realtime -m $(whoami)</code> in a terminal window."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/low-latency.md:25
msgid ""
"Note that this is a fairly drastic solution. It may be better to create a "
"new user account, put *that* user in the `realtime` group, and only log into"
" that user account to run low-latency-critical apps."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/migrate-older.md:0
msgid "Migrate Older Installations"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/migrate-older.md:11
msgid "2024-12-01 image or earlier"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/migrate-older.md:12
msgid ""
"To update a system installed from this or an earlier image, run the "
"following in a terminal window:"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/migrate-older.md:14
msgid ""
"<pre>\n"
"git clone https://invent.kde.org/kde-linux/kde-linux\n"
"cd kde-linux\n"
"run0 ./update.sh update\n"
"</pre>\n"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/migrate-older.md:21
msgid "2025-08-04 image or earlier"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/migrate-older.md:22
msgid ""
"To adopt the erofs-based <code>/usr</code> on a system installed from the "
"2025-08-04 image or earlier, first update to the 2025-08-05 image or later, "
"then create a file named "
"<code>/etc/sysupdate.d/erofs.feature.d/enable.conf</code> containing the "
"following:"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/migrate-older.md:24
msgid ""
"<pre>\n"
"[Feature]\n"
"Enabled=true\n"
"</pre>\n"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/migrate-older.md:29
msgid "And then run:"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/migrate-older.md:30
msgid ""
"<pre>\n"
"run0 /usr/lib/systemd/systemd-sysupdate update\n"
"</pre>\n"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/migrate-older.md:34
msgid ""
"After a reboot, <code>/usr</code> will be a read-only erofs volume, and the "
"rest of <code>/</code> will be writable by the root user."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/migrate-older.md:36
msgid ""
"See [Overview of RootFS v2](https://community.kde.org/KDE_Linux/RootFSv2) "
"for an overview of this change, and manual migration instructions should the"
" automatic migration fail."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/more-software.md:0
msgid "Install Software Not Available in Discover"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/more-software.md:11
msgid ""
"If you don't find the software you're looking for in Discover, there are a "
"few options here, depending on what you want. All of these options are more "
"suitable for advanced users."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/more-software.md:13
msgid "Specific common software"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/more-software.md:14
msgid "DaVinci Resolve"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/more-software.md:15
msgid ""
"DaVinci Resolve is challenging to install. If it meets your needs, consider "
"trying KDE's [Kdenlive](https://kdenlive.org) video editor instead. If not, "
"proceed."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/more-software.md:17
msgid ""
"First, download the DaVinci Resolve software using the official installer at"
" https://www.blackmagicdesign.com/products/davinciresolve. This will get you"
" a <code>.run</code> file. Ignore it for now."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/more-software.md:19
msgid ""
"If you are using an NVIDIA GPU, run the following commands in a terminal "
"window:"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/more-software.md:20
msgid ""
"<pre>\n"
"distrobox create -i ghcr.io/zelikos/davincibox:latest --nvidia -n davincibox\n"
"[drag the .run file into the terminal window, or paste its path here] --appimage-extract\n"
"distrobox enter davincibox -- sudo dnf update\n"
"</pre>\n"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/more-software.md:26
msgid ""
"Otherwise, if you are not using an NVIDIA GPU, run the commands below "
"instead:"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/more-software.md:27
msgid ""
"<pre>\n"
"wget https://raw.githubusercontent.com/zelikos/davincibox/refs/heads/main/setup.sh --directory-prefix=/tmp/\n"
"chmod +x /tmp/setup.sh\n"
"/tmp/setup.sh [drag the .run file into the terminal window, or paste its path here]\n"
"</pre>\n"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/more-software.md:33
msgid "For more information, see https://github.com/zelikos/davincibox/."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/more-software.md:35
msgid "Tailscale"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/more-software.md:36
msgid "Follow one of the following sets of instructions:"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/more-software.md:37
msgid ""
"https://github.com/suikan4github/Using-tailscale-client-on-an-Immutable-OS "
"(Uses Distrobox)"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/more-software.md:38
msgid ""
"https://github.com/xuars/kdelinux-tailscale (Downloads binaries to /opt)"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/more-software.md:40
msgid "Software not listed above"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/more-software.md:41
msgid "Distrobox"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/more-software.md:42
msgid ""
"[Distrobox](https://distrobox.it) is a system for creating “containers” "
"within which you can install anything from the software library of another "
"Linux distribution, in a self-contained manner and with access to the files "
"in your home directory. Distrobox works well for creating bespoke "
"development environments that won't scatter files all over your home "
"directory. Distrobox comes pre-installed in KDE Linux; explore it using the "
"<code>distrobox</code> command-line. [Toolbx](https://containertoolbx.org) "
"is also pre-installed and supported."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/more-software.md:44
msgid "Example usage:"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/more-software.md:46
msgid ""
"<pre>\n"
"# Try to run a command, for example \"mc\"\n"
"mc\n"
"\n"
"# It does not work because is not installed on the system\n"
"# KDE Linux does not include the “mc” command.\n"
"\n"
"# Download the image \"quay.io/toolbx/arch-toolbox\".\n"
"distrobox create -n default\n"
"\n"
"# Enter it\n"
"distrobox enter default\n"
"\n"
"# Do whatever you want in it. Here, we install `mc`\n"
"sudo pacman -Syu\n"
"sudo pacman -S mc\n"
"\n"
"# Run `mc`. Your home directory from KDE Linux is exposed as your home directory inside the Linux container. Press F10 to close mc.\n"
"mc\n"
"\n"
"# Exit the distrobox container\n"
"</pre>\n"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/more-software.md:69
msgid ""
"<pre>\n"
"# To find the container image:\n"
"podman image list\n"
"\n"
"# To see the distrobox podman container still running:\n"
"podman ps\n"
"distrobox list\n"
"distrobox stop default\n"
"\n"
"# To delete the container:\n"
"distrobox rm name\n"
"podman image list # Says \"IMAGE ID\" is 664c1f5776fa.\n"
"podman image rm 664c1f5776fa\n"
"podman image list\n"
"</pre>\n"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/more-software.md:85
msgid "Kapsule"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/more-software.md:86
msgid ""
"{{< section class=\"text-center warning-bubble\" >}} Kapsule is in early "
"development: features, design, and scope may change. {{< /section >}}"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/more-software.md:90
msgid ""
"[Kapsule](https://invent.kde.org/kde-linux/kapsule) is an upcoming tool that"
" aims to seamlessly add command-line tools on top of the base OS in a safe, "
"containerized environment."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/more-software.md:92
msgid ""
"Unlike Distrobox and similar, which require manual setup, Kapsule’s goal is "
"to be invisible to the user and deeply integrate with the OS and terminal "
"apps."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/more-software.md:94
msgid ""
"For the quick start example, see the [project’s "
"README](https://invent.kde.org/kde-linux/kapsule/-/blob/master/README.md), "
"or run <code>kapsule</code> in a terminal to see available commands."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/more-software.md:96
msgid "AppImage"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/more-software.md:97
msgid ""
"Apps packaged as AppImages work in KDE Linux, and many can be found at "
"https://www.appimagehub.com. AppImages offer a reduced level of system "
"integration compared to other software, so getting apps using Discover is "
"preferred."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/more-software.md:99
msgid ""
"If an AppImage app opens the “Choose application to open this file” dialog "
"instead of launching, that means it has not been made executable. Fix it as "
"follows:"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/more-software.md:101
msgid "Right-click on it and select *Properties*"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/more-software.md:102
msgid "Click the *Permissions* tab"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/more-software.md:103
msgid "Click the checkbox that says \"Allow executing file as program\""
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/more-software.md:104
msgid "Click the *OK* button"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/more-software.md:105
msgid "Launch the AppImage file again; now it should run"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/more-software.md:107 content/docs/nix.md:0
msgid "Nix"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/more-software.md:108
msgid ""
"[Nix](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nix_(package_manager)) is an advanced "
"package management tool suitable for use by technically-adept users. Nix "
"facilitates the installation of many commonly-used programs from a [large "
"library of precompiled software](https://search.nixos.org/packages), and "
"takes care of adding command-line tools to your [search "
"path](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/PATH_(variable))."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/more-software.md:110
msgid "See the [Nix](nix) subpage for details."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/more-software.md:112
msgid "Homebrew"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/more-software.md:114
msgid ""
"[Homebrew](https://brew.sh) is an add-on package management system. Homebrew"
" is simple to install and provides a large number of packages, but they may "
"conflict with user-space software and cause unexpected issues."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/more-software.md:116
msgid ""
"Homebrew can be installed using the installation script on the [homebrew "
"homepage](https://brew.sh/). **Do not execute the post-installation commands"
" shown at the end of installation**; KDE Linux includes Homebrew’s `brew` "
"package manager (and anything installed using it) in `PATH` for interactive "
"shells only, to prevent conflicts with system software."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/more-software.md:118
msgid ""
"When you want to access `brew` or anything installed using it, you must "
"first launch a login shell by executing `zsh -l`. You can configure Konsole "
"to launch this by default in *Settings > Manage Profiles*. Create a new "
"profile, enable *Default profile*, and set the command to `zsh -l`."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/more-software.md:120
msgid "Compile it yourself"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/more-software.md:121
msgid ""
"If you can get the dependencies using (for example) Distrobox or Homebrew, "
"you'll be able to [compile anything you want](../dev)."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/more-software.md:123
msgid ""
"To install compiled software to a location that's available system-wide, set"
" the `$DESTDIR` environment variable to `~/kde/usr/` if compiling into a "
"[Systemd extension](/docs/override-usr), or to `/opt/local/` if not."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/multi-gpu.md:0
msgid "Multi-GPU"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/multi-gpu.md:11
msgid ""
"If your computer has more than one graphics card (or “GPU”), most of the "
"time applications that need to do heavy graphical work will automatically "
"use the more powerful GPU."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/multi-gpu.md:13
msgid ""
"If this isn’t working as expected, here are some methods for forcing apps to"
" use the more powerful GPU:"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/multi-gpu.md:16
msgid "Persistent change, using Menu Editor"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/multi-gpu.md:17
msgid ""
"This method will force the app to use the dedicated GPU every time it’s "
"launched from within KDE Plasma or any other app."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/multi-gpu.md:19
msgid "Launch the _Menu Editor_ app"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/multi-gpu.md:20
msgid "In the sidebar, locate the misbehaving app"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/multi-gpu.md:21
msgid "Click the “Advanced” tab"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/multi-gpu.md:22
msgid "Check the “Run using dedicated graphics card” checkbox"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/multi-gpu.md:23
msgid "Click “Save”."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/multi-gpu.md:26
msgid "Persistent change for Steam Games"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/multi-gpu.md:27
msgid ""
"This method will force the game to use the dedicated GPU every time it’s "
"launched from Steam."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/multi-gpu.md:29
msgid "Locate the game on your “Library” page and click it"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/multi-gpu.md:30
msgid "Click the gear icon and select “Properties”"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/multi-gpu.md:31
msgid ""
"If your dedicated GPU is from AMD or Intel, enter:<pre>DRI_PRIME=1 "
"%command%</pre>"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/multi-gpu.md:32
msgid ""
"If your dedicated GPU is from NVIDIA, enter:<pre>__NV_PRIME_RENDER_OFFLOAD=1"
" __VK_LAYER_NV_optimus=NVIDIA_only __GLX_VENDOR_LIBRARY_NAME=nvidia "
"%command%</pre>"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/multi-gpu.md:35
msgid "Temporary change, using the command-line"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/multi-gpu.md:36
msgid ""
"This method will temporarily force the app to use the dedicated GPU right "
"now. The change will not be permanent if you run the app using any other "
"method in the future."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/multi-gpu.md:38
msgid ""
"Choose one option depending on which kind of dedicated GPU the system has, "
"and then run that option’s command in a terminal window:"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/multi-gpu.md:40
msgid ""
"If the dedicated GPU is from AMD or Intel:<pre>DRI_PRIME=1 [the executable "
"name/path of the app]</pre>"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/multi-gpu.md:41
msgid ""
"If the dedicated GPU is from NVIDIA:<pre>prime-run [the executable name/path"
" of the app]</pre>"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/network-shares.md:0
msgid "Access Network Shares"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/network-shares.md:11
msgid ""
"KDE Linux can access disks or “shares” on network servers that use any of "
"the following protocols:"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/network-shares.md:12
msgid "`smb://` (Server Message Block/Samba/SMB)"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/network-shares.md:13
msgid "`nfs://` (Network File System/NFS)"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/network-shares.md:14
msgid "`ftp://` and `sftp://` (File Transfer Protocol/FTP/SFTP)"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/network-shares.md:15
msgid "`webdav://` (WebDAV)"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/network-shares.md:18
msgid "Don’t do this"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/network-shares.md:19
msgid ""
"Many guides on the internet recommend mounting network shares by creating "
"permanent entries for them in the `/etc/fstab` file. **This is not "
"recommended;** when the server becomes unavailable, the system can "
"experience slow boot times, hanging applications, or even data loss."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/network-shares.md:22
msgid "Do this instead"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/network-shares.md:24
msgid "If you already know the server’s address"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/network-shares.md:25
msgid "*This applies to all supported protocols.*"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/network-shares.md:27 content/docs/network-shares.md:36
msgid "Launch the *Dolphin* file manager."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/network-shares.md:28 content/docs/network-shares.md:37
msgid "Click “Network” in the sidebar."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/network-shares.md:29
msgid ""
"In the location field near the top of the window, type the address of the "
"server. For example, to connect to a network share using the SMB protocol "
"with the IP address “192.168.50.72”, type “smb://192.168.50.72”."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/network-shares.md:30 content/docs/network-shares.md:40
msgid "Double-click the desired network share on the server."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/network-shares.md:31 content/docs/network-shares.md:41
msgid ""
"When prompted to authenticate, enter the credentials for accessing the "
"network share."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/network-shares.md:33
msgid "If you know the server exists but don’t know its address"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/network-shares.md:34
msgid "*This only applies to servers using the `smb://` protocol.*"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/network-shares.md:38
msgid "Double-click “Shared Folders (SMB)”."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/network-shares.md:39
msgid "Double-click the entry for the desired server."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/network-shares.md:44
msgid "Bookmark the server for later use"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/network-shares.md:45
msgid ""
"To access the network share from other applications later, bookmark it:"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/network-shares.md:47
msgid ""
"In *Dolphin*, right-click the icon for the network share, or the white "
"background of the window after accessing it."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/network-shares.md:48
msgid "Choose *Add to Places*."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/network-shares.md:50
msgid ""
"The network share will then appear in the sidebar, inside the *Remote* "
"group."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/network-shares.md:52
msgid ""
"To access files on the network share from within an application, open the "
"standard open/save dialog and click on the bookmarked entry for the network "
"share, which appears in the sidebar there as well."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/network-shares.md:54
msgid ""
"To change the bookmarked network share’s name or icon, right-click it, "
"choose “Edit…”, and adjust things to your liking."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/network-shares.md:57
msgid "Known limitations"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/network-shares.md:58
msgid ""
"The instructions above work with almost all applications available in KDE "
"Linux because they use the KDE-provided open/save dialogs, which show "
"bookmarked network shares and know how to access them."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/network-shares.md:60
msgid ""
"However, some older applications use their own open/save dialogs that don’t "
"include your bookmarked network shares. Prominent examples include "
"[Audacity](https://invent.kde.org/kde-linux/kde-"
"linux/-/work_items/71#audacity), [Blender](https://invent.kde.org/kde-"
"linux/kde-linux/-/work_items/71#blender), [GNU Image Manipulation Program "
"(GIMP)](https://invent.kde.org/kde-linux/kde-linux/-/work_items/71#gimp), "
"[Inkscape](https://invent.kde.org/kde-linux/kde-"
"linux/-/work_items/71#inkscape), and "
"[LibreOffice](https://invent.kde.org/kde-linux/kde-"
"linux/-/work_items/71#libreoffice). These applications require network "
"shares to be mounted locally."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/network-shares.md:62
msgid ""
"If you regularly use any of these applications with files on network shares,"
" mounting the shares locally will provide the least painful experience."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/network-shares.md:64
msgid ""
"To do it safely, use the advanced [systemd automount feature, as detailed in"
" this "
"article](https://rayagainstthemachine.net/linux%20administration/systemd-"
"automount/)."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/nix.md:11
msgid ""
"The [Nix package "
"manager](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nix_(package_manager)) is an advanced"
" tool for advanced users that can be used to acquire virtually any free "
"software package you can imagine from its [large, community-maintained "
"repository](https://search.nixos.org/packages)."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/nix.md:13
msgid ""
"It can be installed on KDE Linux for a single-user system. Nix stores "
"software and dependencies under <tt>/nix/store</tt>, and keeps your [search "
"path](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/PATH_%28variable%29) updated "
"automatically as tools are added or removed."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/nix.md:17
msgid "The Nix package manager can be installed for the current user like so:"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/nix.md:19
msgid ""
"<pre>\n"
"sh <(curl --proto '=https' --tlsv1.2 -L https://nixos.org/nix/install) --no-daemon\n"
"</pre>\n"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/nix.md:23
msgid "Log out and back in again, then test:"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/nix.md:25
msgid ""
"<pre>\n"
"nix-shell -p mc emacs-nox  # you are now inside a shell with mc and emacs\n"
"</pre>\n"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/nix.md:29
msgid ""
"Note that when you quit this shell, <code>mc</code> and <code>emacs</code> "
"are no longer in your shell’s search path. See the next section to make such"
" tools available persistently."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/nix.md:31
msgid "See https://nixos.org/download/#nix-install-linux for further details."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/nix.md:34
msgid "Persistent package installations"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/nix.md:35
msgid ""
"Use <code>nix-env -iA</code> or <code>nix-env --install --attr</code> to "
"install packages to <tt>/nix/store</tt> and make them available in your "
"user’s search path:"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/nix.md:37
msgid ""
"<pre>\n"
"$ nix-env -f '<nixpkgs>' -iA mc\n"
"⋮\n"
"building '/nix/store/1q2sh2f178jx9fl37gd9ks85ysfvpwd9-user-environment.drv'...\n"
"</pre>\n"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/nix.md:43
msgid ""
"This creates a new “environment” which contains all the state changes "
"necessary to make the <code>mc</code> package available, and these can be "
"rolled forward or backward. This is the ''real'' appeal of the Nix package "
"management system, but beyond the scope of this guide."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/nix.md:45
msgid "Verify the <code>mc</code> command is now available for your user:"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/nix.md:47
msgid ""
"<pre>\n"
"$ which mc\n"
"/home/username/.nix-profile/bin/mc\n"
"</pre>\n"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/nix.md:52
msgid ""
"Remove packages with <code>nix-env --uninstall</code> or <code>nix-env "
"-e</code>:"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/nix.md:54
msgid ""
"<pre>\n"
"$ nix-env -e mc\n"
"uninstalling 'mc-4.8.33'\n"
"building '/nix/store/rqbghiyds6f7a49qiwi9gmq7bnkgn9qi-user-environment.drv'...\n"
"</pre>\n"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/nix.md:60
msgid ""
"See the section about [[#garbage-collection|garbage collection]] below for "
"how to reclaim space used by packages that you're no longer using."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/nix.md:62
msgid ""
"See https://nix.dev/manual/nix/latest/command-ref/nix-env.html for further "
"details."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/nix.md:65
msgid "Using <code>nix profile</code>"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/nix.md:66
msgid ""
"The <code>nix \\<command\\></code> interface is still technically considered"
" [experimental](https://nix.dev/manual/nix/latest/command-ref/new-"
"cli/nix3-profile.html) (more context on the “experimental” status of "
"<code>nix profile</code> can be found in [this "
"RFC](https://github.com/NixOS/rfcs/pull/136#discussion_r1123895460)), but in"
" practice it’s widely-used, and more ergonomic. Tab-completion and the "
"<code>--help</code> options for the various <code>nix</code> subcommands "
"will also work out of the box on a fresh installation. Like <code>nix-"
"env</code>, <code>nix profile</code> will install packages to "
"<tt>/nix/store</tt> and make them available in your search path, persisting "
"between login sessions."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/nix.md:68
msgid ""
"Here’s a trivial example using <code>nix profile</code> to install the code "
"search tool "
"[<code>ag</code>](https://github.com/ggreer/the_silver_searcher):"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/nix.md:70
msgid ""
"<pre>\n"
"$ mkdir -p ~/.config/nix\n"
"$ cat >> ~/.config/nix/nix.conf &lt;&lt;EOF\n"
"experimental-features = nix-command flakes\n"
"EOF\n"
"\n"
"$ nix search nixpkgs silver searcher\n"
"⋮\n"
"* legacyPackages.x86_64-linux.silver-searcher (2.2.0)\n"
"  Code-searching tool similar to ack, but faster\n"
"\n"
"$ nix profile add nixpkgs#silver-searcher\n"
"$ which ag\n"
"/home/username/.nix-profile/bin/ag\n"
"</pre>\n"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/nix.md:86
msgid "To list installed packages or remove them:"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/nix.md:88
msgid ""
"<pre>\n"
"$ nix profile list\n"
"⋮\n"
"Name:               silver-searcher\n"
"Flake attribute:    legacyPackages.x86_64-linux.silver-searcher\n"
"Original flake URL: flake:nixpkgs\n"
"Locked flake URL:   github:NixOS/nixpkgs/f08e6b11a5ed43637a8ac444dd44118bc7d273b9?narHash=sha256-7vUo0qWCl/rip%2Bfzr6lcMlz9I0tN/8m7d5Bla/rS2kk%3D\n"
"Store paths:        /nix/store/l120si3zsshmf3jr7dkn5dvcj0n586xb-silver-searcher-2.2.0\n"
"\n"
"$ nix profile remove silver-searcher\n"
"</pre>\n"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/nix.md:100
msgid ""
"See the section about [garbage collection](#garbage-collection) below for "
"how to reclaim space used by packages that you're no longer using."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/nix.md:102
msgid ""
"See https://nix.dev/manual/nix/latest/command-ref/new-cli/nix3-profile.html "
"for further details."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/nix.md:105
msgid "Reinstalling Nix"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/nix.md:106
msgid ""
"If you've enabled the “experimental” <code>nix profile</code> feature, "
"you'll need to disable that and delete the state files associated with your "
"user's profile before reinstalling, otherwise you'll get an error message "
"like this:"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/nix.md:108
msgid ""
"<pre>\n"
"error: profile '/home/username/.local/state/nix/profiles/profile' is incompatible with 'nix-env'; please use 'nix profile' instead\n"
"</pre>\n"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/nix.md:112
msgid ""
"{{< section class=\"text-center warning-bubble\" >}} Warning: this will "
"forget any previously-installed packages! {{< /section >}}"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/nix.md:116
msgid ""
"Comment out the <code>experimental-features</code> line in your Nix "
"configuration file, and then delete the profile state directory:"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/nix.md:118
msgid ""
"<pre>\n"
"$ sed -i'' 's/^experimental-features = nix-command flakes$/#&/' ~/.config/nix/nix.conf\n"
"$ rm -rf ~/.local/state/nix/profiles/profile\n"
"</pre>\n"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/nix.md:123
msgid "Now you can repeat the [installation steps](#installation)."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/nix.md:126
msgid ""
"Garbage-collecting to reclaim disk space <span id=\"garbage-"
"collection\"></span>"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/nix.md:127
msgid ""
"Note that <code>nix-env -e</code> and <code>nix profile remove</code> both "
"remove commands provided by a package from your user's current environment, "
"but the software actually remains installed in <tt>/nix/store</tt> until it "
"is garbage collected."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/nix.md:129
msgid ""
"You can force that garbage collection, to reclaim disk space, with one of "
"the following commands:"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/nix.md:131
msgid ""
"<pre>\n"
"nix-store --gc           # routine garbage collection\n"
"nix-collect-garbage -d   # remove \"unreachable\" packages from the store\n"
"</pre>\n"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/nix.md:137
msgid "Removing Nix"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/nix.md:138
msgid "To remove the Nix package manager, run the following commands:"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/nix.md:140
msgid ""
"<pre>\n"
"sudo systemctl disable --now nix-daemon.service nix-daemon.socket\n"
"\n"
"sudo rm -rf /nix /etc/nix /etc/profile.d/nix.sh /etc/tmpfiles.d/nix-daemon.conf /nix /root/.nix-channels /root/.nix-defexpr /root/.nix-profile /root/.cache/nix ~/.nix-channels ~/.nix-defexpr ~/.nix-profile ~/.cache/nix\n"
"\n"
"for i in $(seq 1 32); do sudo userdel nixbld$i; done\n"
"\n"
"sudo groupdel nixbld\n"
"</pre>\n"
msgstr ""

