#: content/docs/override-usr.md:0
msgid "Add or Override Content in /usr"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/override-usr.md:11
msgid ""
"In KDE Linux, <code>/usr</code> is read-only; you cannot modify the "
"contents."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/override-usr.md:13
msgid ""
"However, you can set up an overlay on top of it, and then files you add to "
"this overlay will override files with the same name and location in "
"<code>/usr</code>. To do this, we will use a tool called “Systemd "
"Extensions”, or “sysext” for short."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/override-usr.md:15
msgid "Run the following setup script to set one up:"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/override-usr.md:17
msgid ""
"<pre>\n"
"set-up-systemd-extension\n"
"</pre>\n"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/override-usr.md:21
msgid "After it completes, confirm that the sysext works:"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/override-usr.md:23
msgid ""
"<pre>\n"
"# Verify that it got enabled\n"
"systemd-sysext\n"
"\n"
"# Create a dummy file in the sysext\n"
"echo \"It worked\" > ~/kde/usr/foo\n"
"\n"
"# Refresh the sysext so the system sees the change\n"
"sudo systemd-sysext refresh\n"
"\n"
"# Make sure it appeared in /usr as expected\n"
"cat /usr/foo\n"
"</pre>\n"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/override-usr.md:38
msgid "Disabling the sysext is easy too:"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/override-usr.md:46
msgid ""
"[Official sysext "
"documentation](https://www.freedesktop.org/software/systemd/man/latest/systemd-"
"sysext.html)"
msgstr ""

