#: content/docs/pre-turing-nvidia.md:0
msgid "Use a Pre-Turing (Older than GTX 1630) NVIDIA GPU"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/pre-turing-nvidia.md:11
msgid ""
"These GPUs are limited to the Nouveau graphics drivers, which are pre-"
"installed. However they must be manually enabled. Here's how to do so:"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/pre-turing-nvidia.md:13
msgid "Power on or reboot the system"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/pre-turing-nvidia.md:14
msgid "Repeatedly press the spacebar to make the boot menu appear"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/pre-turing-nvidia.md:15
msgid "On the boot menu, press the <kbd>e</kbd> key"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/pre-turing-nvidia.md:16
msgid "Type ”nomodeset ” (yes, include the trailing space)"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/pre-turing-nvidia.md:17
msgid "Press the <kbd>Enter</kbd> key"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/pre-turing-nvidia.md:18
msgid "Log in, now in low graphics mode"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/pre-turing-nvidia.md:19
msgid ""
"Create a file named <code>/etc/modprobe.d/nvidia-utils.conf</code> with this"
" content: <pre> install nouveau blacklist nvidia </pre>"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/pre-turing-nvidia.md:23
msgid "Now reboot again"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/python-dev.md:0
msgid "Develop or Run Python scripts"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/python-dev.md:11
msgid ""
"KDE Linux includes Python, but without any provision for installing "
"additional system-level modules. Many Python programs require the use of "
"modules that aren’t pre-installed, so how do you resolve this situation?"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/python-dev.md:13
msgid ""
"The solution is to create a virtual environment, within which you can "
"install whatever dependencies you need:"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/python-dev.md:15
msgid ""
"<pre>\n"
"# Create a new virtual environment in the current directory named “venv”\n"
"python -m venv venv\n"
"\n"
"# Activate the “venv” virtual environment\n"
"source venv/bin/activate\n"
"\n"
"# Install what you need\n"
"python -m ensurepip --default-pip\n"
"pip install [whatever Python modules you need]\n"
"\n"
"# run or develop the tool\n"
"\n"
"# Exit the virtual environment\n"
"deactivate\n"
"\n"
"# Optional: delete the “venv” virtual environment if you don’t need it anymore\n"
"rm -r venv\n"
"</pre>\n"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/python-dev.md:36
msgid ""
"{{< section class=\"text-center warning-bubble\" >}} It’s recommended to "
"avoid installing Python using Homebrew, as this will [break kde-"
"builder](https://invent.kde.org/kde-linux/kde-linux/-/issues/278) and "
"potentially any other Python-based software shipped on the system. {{< "
"/section >}}"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/remote-login.md:0
msgid "Log Into the System Remotely"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/remote-login.md:11
msgid ""
"KDE Linux supports two methods of logging in as a user on the system from "
"another system:"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/remote-login.md:12
msgid "Graphically, via Remote Desktop Protocol (or “**RDP**”)."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/remote-login.md:13
msgid "In a terminal window, via Secure Shell (or “**SSH**”)."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/remote-login.md:15
msgid "Graphically using RDP"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/remote-login.md:16
msgid ""
"*This method allows you to interact with the system as if you were using it "
"normally.*"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/remote-login.md:18
msgid "To enable remote access via RDP, do the following:"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/remote-login.md:20
msgid "1. Enable the system for RDP access"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/remote-login.md:21
msgid "Launch the *System Settings* app."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/remote-login.md:22
msgid ""
"In the sidebar, scroll down to the *Security & Privacy* group and click on "
"*Remote Desktop*."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/remote-login.md:23
msgid ""
"Under *System Users*, click on a user account in the list to enable it for "
"remote desktop usage."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/remote-login.md:24
msgid ""
"Click the *Enable RDP server* switch in the top-right corner of the window."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/remote-login.md:25
msgid ""
"One or more network addresses will be listed near the top of the window. "
"Write down at least one of them."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/remote-login.md:26
msgid ""
"To enable the system for remote login every time it’s started up and the "
"user you indicated has logged in, click the *Autostart at login* checkbox."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/remote-login.md:28
msgid "2. Connect via an RDP client app on another system"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/remote-login.md:29
msgid ""
"From another system on the same network, install an RDP client app. To fine "
"some, search for “RDP client” in the other system’s app store/software "
"manager. [KDE makes one called *KRDC*](https://apps.kde.org/krdc/), but "
"others should work as well."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/remote-login.md:30
msgid "Launch the RDP client app."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/remote-login.md:31
msgid ""
"When prompted to enter a server address, type the network address for the "
"remote machine that you wrote down earlier and press the <kbd>Enter</kbd> "
"key."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/remote-login.md:32
msgid ""
"When prompted to enter credentials, type the username of the account you "
"enabled for RDP usage on the remote machine, and its password. Leave the "
"“Domain” field blank."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/remote-login.md:35
msgid "Terminal using SSH"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/remote-login.md:36
msgid ""
"*This method allows you to interact with the system as if you were in a "
"local terminal window.*"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/remote-login.md:38
msgid "1. Enable the system for SSH access"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/remote-login.md:39
msgid "Launch the *Konsole* app."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/remote-login.md:40
msgid ""
"Run `systemctl enable --now sshd`. When prompted to authenticate, do so."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/remote-login.md:41
msgid ""
"Verify that the SSH service has launched by running `systemctl status sshd`."
" If it worked, you'll see “Active: active (running)” mentioned somewhere."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/remote-login.md:42
msgid ""
"Write down the system's IP address by running `ip address`. Look under "
"“inet” under the first entry that is *not* “lo”:"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/remote-login.md:44
msgid ""
"![Depiction of finding the correct IP address](/linux/docs/ip-address.webp)"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/remote-login.md:46
msgid "2. Connect via SSH on another system"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/remote-login.md:47
msgid ""
"From another system on the same network, open a terminal app of your choice."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/remote-login.md:48
msgid ""
"Run `ssh [username of a user on the other system]@[IP address of the other "
"system]`. For example, to log in as the “alex” user on a system whose IP "
"address is “192.168.1.1”, run `ssh alex@192.168.1.1`."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/remote-login.md:49
msgid "When prompted, enter password of the user you specified."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/rip-audio-cds.md:0
msgid "Copy/Rip Audio CDs to Your Computer"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/rip-audio-cds.md:11
msgid ""
"To copy (or “rip”) Audio CDs to your computer, the recommended way on KDE "
"Linux is to use Discover to install <a "
"href=\"https://apps.kde.org/audex/\">Audex</a>, KDE’s application for Audio "
"CD ripping."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/rip-audio-cds.md:13
msgid ""
"Launch Audex and insert a disc into the drive. It will automatically look up"
" and download the disk *metadata* (artist, album name, track names etc.) "
"from <a href=\"https://gnudb.org\">gnudb.org</a>, if available. You can also"
" make manual changes to all metadata."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/rip-audio-cds.md:15
msgid ""
"Common file formats to use for the ripped audio files include **MP3** (small"
" files, good enough quality for most use cases) and **FLAC** (bigger files, "
"\"CD quality\"). You can select your preferred format from the *Profile* "
"drop-down menu on the toolbar."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/rip-audio-cds.md:17
msgid ""
"After choosing an audio profile, click the *Rip* button on the right side of"
" the toolbar! When ripping has finished, the audio files will be placed in a"
" subfolder inside `/home/[your username]/Music` folder. If you want to use a"
" different location or change the naming scheme of the resulting audio "
"files, you can do all that and many more under *Settings > Configure "
"Audex…*."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/roadmap.md:0
msgid "Roadmap & Lifecycle"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/roadmap.md:13
msgid "Roadmap"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/roadmap.md:14
msgid ""
"[Alpha milestone](https://invent.kde.org/groups/kde-linux/-/milestones/3) "
"(Testing edition) - completed on 2025-09-06"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/roadmap.md:15
msgid ""
"[Beta release](https://invent.kde.org/groups/kde-linux/-/milestones/2) "
"(Enthusiast & Stable editions) - in progress"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/roadmap.md:16
msgid ""
"[Public release](https://invent.kde.org/groups/kde-linux/-/milestones/1) "
"(Stable edition) - not started"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/roadmap.md:19
msgid "Lifecycle"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/roadmap.md:20
msgid ""
"Every released version of KDE Linux is guaranteed to be able to update to "
"the latest one for the entire duration of the project — either directly, or "
"by updating to a newer version, and then from that one to the latest "
"version."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/roadmap.md:23
msgid "Support period"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/roadmap.md:24
msgid ""
"Each released version of KDE Linux is supported until the next one is "
"released. Users are expected to update regularly and ensure they are using "
"the latest version."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/ssh-keys.md:0
msgid "Automatically Unlock your SSH Keys"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/ssh-keys.md:11
msgid ""
"If your SSH keys are encrypted, you can configure the system to unlock them "
"automatically in each new terminal window and tab you open."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/ssh-keys.md:13
msgid ""
"To do this, add the following on its own line anywhere in your shell's "
"configuration file (`~/.zshrc` for the default zsh shell, and `~/.bashrc` "
"for bash):"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/ssh-keys.md:15
msgid ""
"<pre>\n"
"ssh-add\n"
"</pre>\n"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/ssh-keys.md:19
msgid ""
"This works because KDE Linux automatically sets up a single-instance SSH "
"agent and populates the required `SSH_AUTH_SOCK` environment variable for "
"instant use."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/ssh-keys.md:21
msgid ""
"Turning it off and setting things up manually is not recommended. If want to"
" do it anyway, mask the relevant systemd service with `systemctl mask --now "
"--user ssh-agent.service`, and then set things up to your taste."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/updates.md:0
msgid "Keep the System Up to Date"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/updates.md:11
msgid ""
"There are two methods of keeping a KDE Linux system up to date: graphical, "
"and using command-line tools."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/updates.md:15
msgid ""
"Updates are done through the _Discover_ software center app. Discover "
"handles both system updates as well as updates for Flatpak-based apps and "
"add-on content."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/updates.md:17
msgid ""
"Discover will notify you when updates are available; just click the "
"notification to launch Discover and see what’s available. On Discover’s "
"Updates page, click “Update All” when you’re ready to update."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/updates.md:19
msgid ""
"Updates to apps take effect the next time the updated apps are launched, "
"while system updates take effect the next time the machine is restarted."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/updates.md:23
msgid ""
"Alternatively, you can update software using command-line tools in a "
"terminal."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/updates.md:25
msgid ""
"Check for Flatpak updates and interactively decide to install them or not "
"using <code>flatpak update</code>."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/updates.md:27
msgid ""
"Check for system updates using <code>updatectl check</code>, and install the"
" latest one with <code>updatectl update</code>. Restart the system to apply "
"the update."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/updates.md:29
msgid ""
"If greater verbosity is needed, or <code>updatectl</code> is not working, "
"use <code>run0 /usr/lib/systemd/systemd-sysupdate update</code> instead. In "
"these cases, record the output and enter it into a bug report at "
"https://invent.kde.org/kde-linux/kde-linux/-/issues/new."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/updates.md:32
msgid "Troubleshooting & known issues"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/updates.md:33
msgid ""
"If updates fail between 30% and 40% with “Input/output error”, wait an hour "
"or two and try again. This is likely to be a [known "
"issue](https://invent.kde.org/kde-linux/kde-linux/-/issues/304) related to "
"updates being advertised as available before all update servers have fully "
"synced."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/ventoy.md:0
msgid "Use Ventoy"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/ventoy.md:11
msgid "Ventoy is not supported for creating installable KDE Linux images."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/ventoy.md:13
msgid ""
"In addition to the technical limitation that Ventoy does not support the "
"boot process that KDE Linux uses, Ventoy’s code [cannot be audited to ensure"
" its security](https://github.com/NixOS/nixpkgs/issues/404663/)."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/ventoy.md:15
msgid ""
"The KDE Linux team recommends avoiding Ventoy. Instead, install KDE Linux on"
" a spare USB flash drive [using the supported steps](install/#1-create-a-"
"live-usb-drive)."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/virtual-cameras.md:0
msgid "Work with Virtual and Remote Cameras"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/virtual-cameras.md:11
msgid ""
"It’s commonly believed that these workflows require the use of the out-of-"
"tree `v4l2loopback` kernel driver, but there are alternative methods that "
"work just as well. These methods work in KDE Linux, too; [read about them "
"here](https://www.ideasonboard.com/news/pipewire-is-the-new-v4l2loopback/)."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/vm.md:0
msgid "Create and Use Virtual Machines"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/vm.md:11
msgid ""
"Probably the easiest way to use virtual machines in KDE Linux is with the "
"_Virtual Machine Manager_ app. Install it and its required QEMU extension by"
" running the following command in a terminal window:"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/vm.md:13
msgid ""
"<pre>\n"
"flatpak install org.virt_manager.virt-manager org.virt_manager.virt_manager.Extension.Qemu\n"
"</pre>\n"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/vm.md:17
msgid ""
"Afterwards, launch the _Virtual Machine Manager_ app, click the “File” menu,"
" and select “Add Connection…”"
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/vm.md:19
msgid ""
"Then click the dropdown menu button next to where it says “Hypervisor:”, "
"select “QEMU/KVM user session”, and then click “OK”."
msgstr ""

#: content/docs/vm.md:21
msgid ""
"Now Virtual Machine Manager is ready to create new virtual machines! To "
"create one, Click “File” and then “New Virtual Machine”, or else the toolbar"
" button that looks like a screen with the play icon in it."
msgstr ""

#: content/help.md:13
msgid "Issue reporting"
msgstr ""

#: content/help.md:14
msgid ""
"Since KDE Linux is in an alpha stage of development, report every issue in "
"an eligible version that you encounter! Developers can then look into fixing"
" it for everyone, and advise you of any relevant workarounds in the "
"meantime."
msgstr ""

#: content/help.md:16
msgid ""
"Make sure the issue still happens in the latest version before reporting it "
"to the developers or requesting help from them."
msgstr ""

#: content/help.md:18
msgid ""
"**To report issues in the KDE Linux operating system itself** (i.e. OS "
"design, integration, system services, etc), [use "
"invent.kde.org](https://invent.kde.org/kde-linux/kde-"
"linux/-/work_items/new), and ignore the scary red banner at the top of the "
"page."
msgstr ""

#: content/help.md:22
msgid "Support resources"
msgstr ""

#: content/help.md:23
msgid ""
"KDE Linux is run by passionate volunteers who are eager to help with non-"
"bug-related issues you may encounter, but make no guarantees about their "
"ability to do so in a timely matter, to any level of success, or at all. All"
" such resources are provided on an “as available, best effort” basis."
msgstr ""

#: content/help.md:25
msgid "Help is available in various forms:"
msgstr ""

#: content/help.md:26
msgid ""
"**To get official answers to common questions**, [read the "
"documentation](/docs)."
msgstr ""

#: content/help.md:27
msgid ""
"**To get help with a problem using KDE Linux**, [use "
"discuss.kde.org](https://discuss.kde.org/), and tag your post with “kde-"
"linux”."
msgstr ""

#: content/help.md:28
msgid ""
"**To talk with the KDE Linux developers about issues that may be bugs**, "
"[use Matrix](https://matrix.to/#/%23kde-linux:kde.org)."
msgstr ""

#: content/nvidia.md:0
msgid "The NVIDIA Situation"
msgstr ""

#: content/nvidia.md:10
msgid ""
"NVIDIA GPUs using an architecture older than Turing (this means anything "
"older than GTX 1630) require NVIDIA’s proprietary kernel modules. These "
"modules cannot be loaded at runtime because the base OS is immutable, and "
"pre-installing them appears to be in a [legal gray "
"area](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Linux_kernel#Loadable_kernel_modules). "
"To be safe, KDE Linux doesn’t include them."
msgstr ""

#: content/nvidia.md:12
msgid ""
"Newer NVIDIA GPUs (Turing/GTX 1630 and newer) can use NVIDIA’s open kernel "
"modules which are redistributable with the base OS in a legally clear "
"manner, so KDE Linux pre-installs them. Necessary NVIDIA userspace drivers "
"and utilities are also pre-installed, so these GPUs should work without "
"drama."
msgstr ""

#: content/nvidia.md:14
msgid ""
"Older NVIDIA GPUs *should* work with the less-performant Nouveau drivers, "
"which are included. However support for this must be manually enabled right "
"now, and is not recommended for non-experts. Follow [the "
"instructions](/docs/pre-turing-nvidia), and temper your expectations "
"accordingly."
msgstr ""
